<SECOND>PM-VP Wimps,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fight Wimpdom, Abolish Vice Presidency, Professor Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The vice presidency converts respectable politicians into champagne-sipping wimps and ought to be abolished, a political scientist says. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Gormley </PERSON> said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>, <PERSON> Hubert </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON> and <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> were examples of vigorous congressmen who became victims of a job that has little authority. <PERSON> Gormley </PERSON>, an associate director of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Robert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> M. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Follette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION>, also said the office is outmoded because the founding fathers conceived of the vice presidency as an advisory post Yet presidents today have plenty of advisers, he said. Worst of all, <PERSON> Gormley </PERSON> said, is the effect the vice presidency has on the people who hold the office. `` The vice presidency turns a vigorous, robust individual into a wimp,'' he said. `` After a few years as vice president, even a previously vigorous and creative political leader turns into a wishy-washy, mealy-mouthed sycophant.'' `` Vice presidents have always been wimps. <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>, <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> were all wimpy vice presidents,'' he said. `` In order to do the job as vice president, they must play the role of a meek and humble servant, a presidential loyalist, a defender of the president's position,'' he said. The country could easily turn to the secretary of state or the speaker of the House of Representatives for a successor if a president were to die in office, he said. The secretary of state also could perform many of the vice president's functions, he said. `` The secretary of state can sip champagne at diplomatic parties and look somber and dignified at state funerals,'' <PERSON> Gormley </PERSON> said. `` The vice president is eminently dispensable.''
</TEXT>
