<HEAD>Police Arrest Lebanese Gunman After Standoff At Libyan Embassy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police ended a nearly 12-hour standoff with an armed Lebanese man barricaded in the Libyan Embassy by rushing in and grabbing the gunman after he had fallen asleep, officials said. No shots were fired in the incident Thursday, and a handful of Libyan embassy employees who had been trapped on the top floors were not injured, police said. Police identified the man as <PERSON> El-Ibrahim </PERSON> <PERSON> Edelbi </PERSON>, 22, and said he had escaped from a prison in <LOCATION> Goettingen </LOCATION> on July 8 along with a <LOCATION> Turkish </LOCATION> accomplice who has since been recaptured. <PERSON> Edelbi </PERSON> was serving a three-year prison term for assault, police said. For nearly 12 hours police negotiated with <PERSON> Edelbi </PERSON>, who pulled out a pistol inside the embassy's first-floor reception room after he was denied a visa for <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>. Embassy employees were able to flee the building quickly or run to the upper floors, leaving <PERSON> Edelbi </PERSON> by himself, police said. `` He had become very weak since his escape and looked exhausted during the negotiations,'' said <PERSON> Ulrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Fischer </PERSON>, head of the <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION> police team that captured <PERSON> Edelbi </PERSON>. <PERSON> Fischer </PERSON>'s team was able to watch <PERSON> Edelbi </PERSON> by making use of a video camera that is a normal part of embassy security. At about 9:15 p.m., police noticed <PERSON> Edelbi </PERSON> had fallen asleep and they rushed him, <PERSON> Fischer </PERSON> said. `` Finally, he just fell asleep from exhaustion,'' said <PERSON> Fischer </PERSON>. `` He did not offer us any resistance.'' Police said they did not know where <PERSON> Edelbi </PERSON> got the pistol. <PERSON> Edelbi </PERSON> was taken to a local hospital for examination, officials said. A team of police officers negotiated with the gunman for almost 12 hours by telephone as well as through a metal-barred door at the entrance to the structure. `` He demanded that he not be returned to prison. He said he wanted to go to <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> because the Libyans always help the Lebanese,'' said <PERSON> Fischer </PERSON>. Police spokesman <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> Georg </PERSON> <PERSON> Classen </PERSON> said <PERSON> Edelbi </PERSON> was born in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. But he said <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION> police did not know how long <PERSON> Edelbi </PERSON> had lived in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, whether he had any relatives in this country or know any other details about the man other than his prison record. <PERSON> Edelbi </PERSON> had been at the prison in <LOCATION> Goettingen </LOCATION> for about 18 months, <PERSON> Classen </PERSON> said. Shortly after the standoff began, heavily armed police officers wearing combat gear climbed through a second-story window into the embassy, known as the <ORGANIZATION> Libyan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>. Those officers guarded access to the upper floors of the five-story building in case <PERSON> Edelbi </PERSON> tried to take hostages from among the employees on the higher floors, <PERSON> Fischer </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Omar </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bukhries </PERSON>, head of the embassy, had given police permission to enter the building, <PERSON> Classen </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bukhries </PERSON> was able to escape through a side door shortly after the standoff began. Police sealed off the area after embassy employees signaled an alarm shortly before 10 a.m.
