<HEAD>Gorbachev's Poland Tour: A Reporter's Notebook</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland-Gorbachev, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> made his way around <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> this week, he fell further and further behind schedule, leaving thousands of people who had been invited to see him waiting for hours _ sometimes in vain. The Soviet leader arrived in the western port city of <LOCATION> Sczcecin </LOCATION> on Wednesday already an hour behind schedule, and by the time he reached his first scheduled event, a speech at a shipyard, he was two hours late. Polish authorities, anxious to ensure all went smoothly for their Soviet visitor, had seated the workers nearly two hours ahead of time. So when <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> finally arrived, the 3,000 people in the audience were squirming after sitting practically silent on backless wooden benches for four hours. Organizers of the trip kept adding events to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s schedule, including a visit to a private farm on his way to the airport to return to <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> It was nearly midnight when the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief arrived back in the capital, just about four hours late. The delay forced cancellation of a special chamber music concert that had been arranged for <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Raisa </PERSON>, in a palace on the outskirts of the capital. Although most of the unannounced stops had been arranged in advance, with state-run television often set up to record the events, Polish government spokesman <PERSON> Jerzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Urban </PERSON> attributed the delays to what he called <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s extraordinary popularity among the Polish people. Never before, he said, had a visitor drawn such crowds or generated so much `` spontaneous joy.'' But at all those events reporters were permitted to witness, the crowds were screened in advance, and Polish security often checked peoples' invitations against their identification cards before permitting them within sight of the Soviet leader.
