<SECOND>PM-Cosmetics,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Few Controls On Ingredients, FDA Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Americans have indicated they would like to see more federal regulation of the $ 17 billion-a-year cosmetic industry, which currently lacks stringent controls, an official of the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> says. <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Eiermann </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>'s division of cosmetic technology, said people are often surprised to learn that cosmetics, which usually contain chemicals, have so few federal guidelines. <PERSON> Eiermann </PERSON> made his comments in a telephone interview Thursday after a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee heard testimony about the potential danger of some of the chemicals in cosmetics. Rep. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyden </PERSON>, D-Ore., chairman of the small business panel, said some of the chemicals in cosmetics can cause cancer, birth defects, central nervous disorders, skin and eye irritations and allergic reactions <PERSON> Wyden </PERSON> promised to have additional hearings in the fall to weigh whether <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should take action to enforce additional testing and labeling of cosmetics. About 8,000 chemicals are used in cosmetics and perfume. He said the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> does not have the authority to test cosmetics for safety before they are sold, and can not require manufacturers to provide test data on a product's safety. The only actions <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> can take are to seize contaminated products and to ask manufacturers to change their advertising claims, he said. Retail products sold to consumers must be labeled as to contents, but that regulation does not apply to products sold to business establishments, such as hair styling salons. <PERSON> Eiermann </PERSON> said it is <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' responsibility to decide whether Americans want cosmetics to be subject to the same standards applied to food and drugs. But he said the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> did a food survey in the 1970s and included questions about cosmetics. `` There is a preponderance of the population ... they think the products should be regulated,'' he said. Results of the study were never published because they were part of the broader survey, he said. The Cosmetic, Toiletry and <ORGANIZATION> Fragrance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, a group that represents the industry, said cosmetic companies are committed to safety. `` Because of this commitment, personal care products are among the safest of any consumer products and are used confidently by millions of persons on a daily basis,'' it said in a statement The industry has a program of self-regulation that involves testing ingredients, the statement said. <PERSON> Beth </PERSON> <PERSON> Shulman </PERSON>, vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should pass legislation requiring that all cosmetic products contain ingredient labels. Secondly, she said, more studies need to be done to determine the long-term effects on people who use the chemicals. Dr. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Cone </PERSON>, chief of the occupational health clinic at <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> General </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, urged <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to take steps to warn consumers and beauticians about any possible health hazards in cosmetics. He suggested that products contain detailed labels that clearly spell out the nature of any chemicals in the cosmetics and explain possible health hazards. Moreover, the government should collect better information about the chemicals and their effects and remove any that are deemed dangerous, <PERSON> Cone </PERSON> said.
