<FIRST>r i PM-Peru-Violence     07-15 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Peru-Violence ,0359</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's largest private television stations began limiting coverage of guerrilla violence in a bid to encourage peace, and the government prolonged a state of emergency to combat the rebels. Also Thursday, Maoist rebels from the group known as Shining Path shot to death the city administrator of <LOCATION> Chincha </LOCATION>, 120 miles south of <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>, police said. Television coverage of <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s eight-year rebel insurgency had become a battle ground among stations in ratings wars, with some channels dedicating up to 15 minutes a night to violent footage. `` The accord of a minute'' was agreed to by <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> channels 2, 4, 5 and 9 _ most of the city's stations. It calls for the time alloted to local news reports of violence held to 60 seconds per broadcast. Channel 5 press director <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Paz </PERSON> said the goal of the self-imposed pact was to contribute to national pacification. President <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> prolonged a state of emergency for two months in the coastal capital of <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> and parts of six other states in the <LOCATION> Andes </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> jungle. The announcement was made in a decree in the official gazette <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peruano </LOCATION>. Police said three Shining Path guerrilla gunmen killed administrator <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Casas </PERSON>, a member of <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>'s center-left <ORGANIZATION> Aprista </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, near his <LOCATION> Chincha </LOCATION> home and escaped before authorities arrived. The official was leaving home for work. The assassination was carried out like dozens of others by the rebel band against government and party officials. But most of the more than 10,000 people slain during the insurgency have been highland peasants caught in the fighting between guerrillas and government forces. The state of emergency was first imposed in highland <LOCATION> Ayacucho </LOCATION> two years after the Shining Path, inspired by the late <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Zedong </PERSON>, launched its insurgency there in 1980 to topple <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s elected government and install Marxist rule. A state of emergency suspends citizens' rights to meet publicly and travel freely, while permitting government forces to conduct searches without warrants and hold suspects for long periods before filing charges.
