<SECOND>PM-Nominee Rejection,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>GOP Gives up Bid to Confirm Reagan Judicial Nominee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Republicans say they'll `` make no effort'' to wage a floor fight for <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Siegan </PERSON>, a conservative appellate court nominee whose writings were cited as too extreme to win Democratic backing. In a vote that had similarities to the rejection last year of <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> nominee <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bork </PERSON>, the Democratic-led <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> voted 8-6 along party lines Thursday to recommend <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> rejection of <PERSON> Siegan </PERSON>. The professor of constitutional law at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diego </ORGANIZATION> was President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s nominee for the 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>, covering nine Western states. Like <PERSON> Bork </PERSON>, <PERSON> Siegan </PERSON> wrote often on the law, and _ like <PERSON> Bork </PERSON> _ his views often were contrary to precedents set by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, especially on civil rights and civil liberties. But while senators decided a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> nominee deserved a full <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> vote, even <PERSON> Siegan </PERSON>'s supporters said no such effort would be made for him. Sen. <PERSON> Strom </PERSON> <PERSON> Thurmond </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-S.C. </LOCATION>, whose motion to report the nomination without recommendation failed on a 7-7 tie, said afterwards that Republicans `` will make no effort to take it to the floor. It's obvious that it's over.'' Sen. <PERSON> Orrin </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>, R-Utah and another <PERSON> Siegan </PERSON> supporter, agreed that there would be no floor fight. Sen. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> DeConcini </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ariz </LOCATION>. first voted for rejection, but then sided with the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> no-recommendation motion Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., who offered the motion to reject <PERSON> Siegan </PERSON>, criticized the nominee's almost total lack of experience before federal courts _ he had one case three decades ago _ and said the nominee practiced `` judicial activism in the extreme. Sen. <PERSON> Arlen </PERSON> <PERSON> Specter </PERSON>, R-Pa., agreed that <PERSON> Siegan </PERSON>'s writings were `` extreme'' but voted for him anyway, arguing a law professor should have freedom to write what he chooses <PERSON> Specter </PERSON>, who opposed <PERSON> Bork </PERSON>, said he would be more concerned about <PERSON> Siegan </PERSON>'s views if he were a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> nominee. An appellate court candidate would have no choice but to follow <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rulings, he said _ a point <PERSON> Siegan </PERSON> made in two confirmation hearings. <PERSON> Siegan </PERSON> wrote that prayer in schools could be constitutional, although the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has said otherwise. He contended that equal weight should be given to property rights and human rights. He said framers of the 14th Amendment, which guarantees basic freedoms, never intended its scope to be as broad as that defined by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Siegan </PERSON> also disagreed with the high court's reasoning in its 1954 decision outlawing school segregation, although he agreed with the result. The landmark ruling, <PERSON> Siegan </PERSON> said, should have been based on the right of black students to travel to the schools of their choice. His critics said this would have left students at the schoolhouse door, without guaranteeing a seat inside. <PERSON> Siegan </PERSON>, 63, was only the second judicial nominee to be rejected by the <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> since the Democrats regained control in January 1987. <PERSON> Bork </PERSON> was the first. Although the two men disagreed on some areas of the law, both wrote often from their positions as law school scholars. <PERSON> Bork </PERSON> went on to become a federal appellate judge, although he resigned after his defeat for the high court. <PERSON> Siegan </PERSON>, after a state court practice, went on to become a professor. His lack of federal court experience was cited by Democrats opposing him. `` He has n't handled a case since I was 12 years old _ 36 years ago,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON>, D-Vt. The 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> has jurisdiction over <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guam </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mariana </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>.
