<HEAD>Bentsen: Campaign Won't Lure Me Away from Trade Battle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democrat <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> is promising to keep up his push for trade legislation even though he expects to spend considerable time on the vice presidential campaign trail. `` I'll be taking some of my time to work on that trade bill here in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>,'' the Texan said Thursday at a meeting of his <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. He said he had `` talked to Governor <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> on that'' and received approval to keep working on the trade measure. The measure was approved by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday and sent to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, where there could be floor action before mid-August. The decision by <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> to tap <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> as his running mate heightens prospects for <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approval of the legislation, in the view of some Democrats. In related action, a legislative blueprint for implementing the U.S.-Canadian free trade agreement won approval Thursday from the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. The plan also cleared the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. Tariffs between the two nations would be phased out over the next 10 years under the agreement. Under special procedures reserved for international trade pacts, the administration will now introduce implementing legislation that follows closely the blueprint drawn up by the two committees. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> guarantees in turn that the legislation gets speeded up consideration, with amendments ruled out. Administration officials promised the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> that the legislation would not include subsidies for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> uranium industry, which had been delaying action by the two committees. Both <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, D-Ill., balked at the uranium subsidy plan Other squabbles also were settled and officials said the path appeared clear for approval of the agreement and the bill. `` We've set an example for the entire world on what can be accomplished with free trade,'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said. `` This is a historic moment.'' <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> issued a statement saying the lawmakers had `` reached agreement among ourselves and with the administration on the details of the implementing legislation.'' `` I believe that this consultative process has developed a sound, well crafted implementing bill, which balances all interests,'' he said. `` It fully carries out our obligations under the agreement but also protects the legitimate intrerests of those few industries concerned about possible adverse effects on their current business dealings,'' he said.
