<HEAD>Reagan Says ``We Can Help To Ease The Pain''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, back from a look at what he called the `` worst natural disaster since the Dust Bowl,'' is sending a team headed by Secretary of Agriculture <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> on a tour of 11 drought-stricken states from <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> Dakotas </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> inspected corn and soybean fields in southern <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> on Thursday and appealed to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to focus its attention on drought relief, putting aside partisanship and efforts to rewrite the overall farm laws. `` Politics must stop at the parched field's edge,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Davenport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, paraphrasing a traditional foreign policy slogan that partisanship should stop at the water's edge. The president spoke at a luncheon in <LOCATION> Davenport </LOCATION> after inspecting crop damage at the <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Quoin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fair </ORGANIZATION> grounds and the nearby farm of <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> <PERSON> Krone </PERSON> near <LOCATION> Marion </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION> `` We should keep our eye on the ball,'' he told the luncheon audience. `` Drought relief should be just that, drought relief.'' Both in <LOCATION> Davenport </LOCATION> and at the fair grounds, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> urged the lawmakers to avoid amendments not relevant to the drought crisis. `` What I saw was not a pretty sight,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said after walking through the shriveled fields and viewing them from a helicopter. `` We ca n't make it rain but we can help to ease the pain, and that's what the federal government will do,'' he told state agriculture officials and farmers gathered at the fair grounds. `` From <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, from <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, and right here in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, farmers face the worst natural disaster since the Dust Bowl of the 1930s,'' the president said. On Air Force One flying back to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> said he and his task force plan to visit 11 states, beginning next Tuesday. He listed <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>. He said he would be accompanied by representatives of the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> and several other agencies. Meanwhile in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> approved a $ 5.5 billion drought relief bill after adopting 10 amendments. The corresponding committee of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> is considering a similar bill. <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> told reporters that the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill appeared to be `` pretty close to the package we've been talking about.'' In <LOCATION> Davenport </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> spoke at a luncheon sponsored by <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Station </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> WOC </ORGANIZATION> and the local chamber of commerce after taking part in 65th anniversary observances of the station, where he began his entertainment career as an announcer in t