 his proven ability to work with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, and his exposure through the years to various heads of state. A senator since 1970, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> is being opposed in his re-election bid this year by Rep. <PERSON> Beau </PERSON> <PERSON> Boulter </PERSON>, a Republican who has been fighting an uphill battle in the race. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> is legally allowed to run for both races under a law passed in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> that allowed <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> to run for vice president with <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> as well as the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> could remove his name from the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> ballot before Sept. 6, but the Democrats could not replace him. <PERSON> Boulter </PERSON> says <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>'s dual candidacy is unethical. If <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> wins both elections, he would have to choose one post or the other. If he gave up his <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> seat, as expected, Republican Gov. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Clements </PERSON> would name an interim senator and then call a special election to pick someone to complete the six-year term. Already, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> politicians were moving to stake out a possible candidacy in the event of such a special election. Lt. Gov. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Hobby </PERSON> said he would `` certainly seriously consider'' running if such a special election takes place. State Agriculture Commissioner <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hightower </PERSON> also said he'd consider a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> race. <PERSON> Hightower </PERSON> already had been looking at a 1990 race against Republican Sen. <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Gramm </PERSON>. Among other Democrats looking to enter the fray are former Gov. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON