<FIRST>r w PM-Drought-Diversion     07-15 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drought-Diversion,480</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Army Engineers Reject Diversion of Great Lakes Water to
Mississippi</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> says it turned down a request for emergency diversion of Great Lakes water to the drought-depleted <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> because the action would do little to help shipping. The decision was based on analysis of water flow and economic considerations, said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Page </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s assistant secretary for civil works, after testifying Thursday before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> merchant marine subcommittee. `` It was not politically motivated,'' Page said. Illinois Gov. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> and other officials whose states have an economic stake in the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> asked last month for an increase in water flow from the lakes to the river from 3,000 cubic feet per second to 10,000 cubic feet per second. They asked that the increased flow continue for 100 days. The officials said increasing the flow would enable barge traffic to resume movement down the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>. The river's level has fallen because of the drought, and some 3,000 barges were reported stranded as a result. Barge shippers have estimated losses as a result of the stalled shipping at up to $ 60 million. But Page said increasing the outflow to 10,000 cubic feet per second would not do much to help <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> navigation, and shoals would continue to impede the flow of goods. `` We will still have flow'' on the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>'' through the summer, he said. `` We see in the foreseeable future based on our forecast we do n't need -LRB- increased diversion -RRB- at all.'' <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Vonnahme </PERSON>, director of water resources for the <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION>, said the agency had no problems with the decision. `` If they feel the waters would n't do any good, then we certainly would n't want to take them out of the lake,'' he said. Great Lakes state senators praised the decision. The corps' position `` gives us more ammunition in the continuing struggle to prevent any diversion,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> Democrat. `` I have maintained that we should explore alternatives to diversion, such as lightening the loads on barges or utilizing truck or rail for transporting goods.'' Sen. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> Democrat, said `` this decision will let us protect our water, conserve it, and use it in the proper ways in the future.'' The governors of four Great Lakes states opposed the diversion, and only <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> supported it among the leaders of the eight states surrounding the lakes. Canadian officials also protested the proposed diversion. Supporters of diversion argued the increased flow out of the lakes would have a minuscule impact on the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> but would have great benefits downriver. Opponents argued that the lakes water was needed in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Northeast </ORGANIZATION>, increasing diversion would set an unacceptable precedent, and the federal government could not increase diversion without the concurrence of all eight governors of Great Lakes states.
</TEXT>
