<FIRST>r w PM-Congress-Drought     07-15 0696</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-Drought,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagan Expected to Sign Disaster Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> appears all but certain to sign a disaster bill containing payments of up to $ 100,000 for drought-stricken farmers, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> chairman says. `` The prospects are virtual certitude that there will be a drought bill,'' Sen. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON>, D-Vt., said Thursday after the committee approved a blueprint that could cost up to $ 7 billion or even more `` We assured the president that we would stay within the budget and we will,'' <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said after touring drought-stricken <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> cornfields with Gov. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> that he was `` a little edgy'' about proposed amendments that flooded into the Agriculture Committees Wednesday night. But he said he stood ready to approve the basic legislation. `` I will sign it the minute it is delivered to me,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said in an interview on radio station <ORGANIZATION> WOC </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Davenport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>. He said in a speech that lawmakers should not use the bill as an excuse to rewrite farm programs. `` Drought relief should be just that, drought relief,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. `` Partisanship should be kept out of the issue of drought relief. Politics must stop at the parched field's edge.'' The government, meanwhile, declared <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> disaster areas because of the drought, making farmers in those states eligible for emergency low-interest loans, officials from both states said. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Dayley </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, said the disaster designation had been requested by the governors of the two states. Other states logged as of Thursday for official designation were: <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON> and Sen. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lugar </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ind </LOCATION>., said at a news conference that best-guess estimates placed the cost of aid to crop growers at around $ 5.5 billion and to livestock producers at $ 1 billion to $ 1.5 billion Overall drought costs, however, could be considerably higher than that, with farm analysts saying the cost of an avalanche of federal crop insurance claims alone could reach $ 1 billion. The bill would provide farmers with disaster payments capped at $ 100,000 for 65 percent of pre-drought expected earnings on crop losses in excess of 35 percent of their historical yields. And both committees are studying ways to enrich the formula a bit for the hardest hit farmers in the Grain Belt. In putting on the finishing touches, senators added special provisions that could aid key industries. One such plan would allow corn refiners who produce ethanol fuel to buy corn from federal stocks at 110 percent of the government's cost of acquisition Influenced by drought, crop prices have skyrocketed since much of the corn was acquired. Under the bill, ethanol producers could buy up to 2 million bushels each every month. Senators said the bill's costs could be offset by government savings, primarily a reduction in deficiency payments due to the drought. These payments to growers of wheat, corn, cotton, rice and a few other crops represent the difference between the value of a farmer's harvest at the market and its value at a so-called target price set by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The budget calls for $ 17 billion in spending by the government-owned <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> for deficiency payments and price-support loans. But the market price of corn is now more than the target price and that would automatically mean a dramatic slash in program costs the market prices held for the rest of the year. Even if not, though, the cost to the government is going to be much smaller than expected. Estimates of the savings range from $ 5 billion to $ 10 billion. Many farmers, however, already have received up to 40 percent of their deficiency payments in advance and, unless rescued by legislation, will have to refund all or part at a time when they have much reduced income. The bill would allow them to keep what they have received in advance. Emergency feed programs for livestock producers would be expanded and capped at $ 50,000 for each individual, and a planned 50-cent per hundredweight cut in dairy price supports set for next year would be called off.
</TEXT>
