<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON>, charged with air piracy and murder in the 1985 <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> hijacking to <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, said a Lebanese group called the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Martyrs </ORGANIZATION> paid for his visit to Islamic holy places in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON>, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, told the court Thursday that he visited Islamic holy sites at <LOCATION> Qom </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mashhad </LOCATION>, traveling via <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>. Asked by the judge to give a date for his trip, <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> first said he could not remember but later said it could have been in 1985. <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> has said he spent two years as a fighter with the Amal militia in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, but has repeatedly denied being a member of <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, a radical, Iran-backed Shiite Moslem group in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. The group is believed to be an umbrella organization for kidnappers holding foreign hostages in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. One of <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON>'s brothers, <PERSON> Abdul-Hadi </PERSON>, is <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>'s security chief The <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> jetliner was hijacked in June 1985 on a flight from <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> diver <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Waldorf </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, was shot and killed after the hijackers forced the plane to land in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. Thirty-nine Americans were held hostage during the 17-day ordeal. A court document introduced Thursday also indicated that <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> was being sought on a murder charge in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> in 1983. The document, read by Chief Judge <PERSON> Heiner </PERSON> <PERSON> Mueckenberger </PERSON>, gave no details. <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> said he was not aware of the charges. The document was obtained after West German federal investigators asked authorities in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> for assistance in their investigation of <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON>. <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON>'s defense attorneys questioned the value of the document as evidence, saying it was an unsigned telex with few details. <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> also said that he smuggled explosives into <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> because he was afraid of `` committing a sin'' against <ORGANIZATION> Islam </ORGANIZATION>. `` I did not say no because I'm a Moslem and its my duty to obey those who are wiser,'' <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> said, referring to a man he said ordered him to smuggle liquid explosives into <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. `` The Koran says obey Allah, obey the prophet and obey those who give you orders. I was afraid of committing a sin if I did not accept.'' He refused to identify the man who ordered him to smuggle the explosives. On Wednesday, <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> admitted bringing explosives into <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> on two occasions. He was arrested at <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> airport in January 1987 when liquid explosives were found in his luggage, but he said he had succeeded in smuggling another shipment a few weeks earlier. In other testimony, <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> said he fought in southern <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> against <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> forces and took part in street battles in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> against `` government soldiers'' and Christian Phalangist militiamen in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> between 1984 and 1987. He said he had been wounded in the arm by a bullet in streeting fighting in 1985, but could not remember if his arm was still in a cast in June, when the hijacking took place. <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> has testified that he was a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moslem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION> militia from 1980 to 1982. He said he also took part in fighting during that period. He arrived in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> late in 1982 and applied for political asylum, but returned to <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> in November 1984 after his request was turned down. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> last year rejected a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> request for <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON>'s extradition A <LOCATION> Duesseldorf </LOCATION> court sentenced one of his brothers, <PERSON> Abbas </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON>, to 13 years in prison in April for the January 1987 kidnappings of two West Germans in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> in an attempt to gain <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON>'s freedom. The trial is scheduled to continue on Tuesday.
