<HEAD>Pasta Resistance: Italy Loses Its Noodle Rule</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The land of pure pasta and taut tortellini is afraid that Italians wo n't be using the old noodle anymore. <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, the mecca of macaroni since the days of <PERSON> Marco </PERSON> <PERSON> Polo </PERSON>, is bracing for what purists say will be an invasion of rubbery ravioli, squishy spaghetti and, heaven forbid, limp linguine. `` In the coming weeks, Italians will have to say goodbye to their beloved firm pasta,'' said the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Repubblica </ORGANIZATION>. On Thursday, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> lost its bid to maintain its so-called `` pasta purity'' law, a 1967 rule requiring all pasta sold in the country to contain durum wheat, which is firmer and more expensive than other varieties of wheat. The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> ruled that <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> could not use the law to block pasta imports from the other 11 Common Market nations, even though <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> still can compel its own pasta makers to use durum wheat. `` That flavorful and firm macaroni, the product of our able pasta makers, will be challenged, and maybe even replaced, by the gluey and insipid pasta from <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Holland </LOCATION>,'' <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Repubblica </ORGANIZATION> moaned. Italians have been eating pasta for at least 700 years and claim it was brought to <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> by <PERSON> Marco </PERSON> <PERSON> Polo </PERSON>. It is always cooked `` al dente,'' or firm. `` We have a profound respect for pasta,'' said <PERSON> Giuseppe </PERSON> <PERSON> Menconi </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Italian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZAT