<HEAD>Sandinista Crackdown Spurs Dissidents, Congress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The leftist Sandinista government's violent crackdown on its critics has backfired and given new momentum to opponents, dissidents say `` These actions are going to strengthen the attitude of the common people who do n't want this regime,'' said <PERSON> Virgilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Godoy </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> labor minister and the president of the <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. `` This is the start of the opposition moving from words to actions.'' Meanwhile, President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said that any <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> decision to resume arms shipments to the Contra rebels would revive a war in which a truce was declared months ago. `` We hope they -LRB- the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> -RRB- do not commit this madness, since it would be newly legitimizing'' the civil war, <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said Thursday on state-run Voice of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> radio. During the crackdown this week, the government broke up a demonstration, closed independent news outlets and expelled the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador. The fallout continued Thursday, when the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> voted 385-18 to condemn <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>'s government for `` brutal suppression of basic human rights.'' A similar resolution was passed Wednesday by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. That measure included the possibility of military aid to the Contras if present Sandinista policy does not become more democratic. `` It's tremendously interventionist and illegal,'' Deputy Foreign Minister <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Tinoco </PERSON> said of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> resolution. `` We call this imperialism.'' <PERSON> Tinoco </PERSON> defended the crackdown as a response to growing threats from the Contras and from attempts to destabilize the government. `` We ca n't take this with our arms folded,'' he said in an interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. `` What country in the world would n't take measures?'' On Sunday, government troops used tear gas and truncheons to crush a demonstration by 100,000 people in <LOCATION> Nandaime </LOCATION>, south of <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>. The government said 31 demontrators were sentenced to six-month jail terms on Thursday for violating public security laws. Five others received the same sentences on Wednesday. On Monday, the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> expelled <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Melton </PERSON> and seven diplomats, charging them with crimes against the Nicaraguan people and saying they authored a destabilization plan that included the Sunday march. At the same time, the government closed the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> radio station and suspended for 15 days the only opposition newspaper, <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION>. `` The free press was used as part of the destabilization plan,'' <PERSON> Tinoco </PERSON> said. <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Prensa </PERSON> repeatedly attacked the government. The newspaper had backed the Sandinistas when they came to power in a 1979 revolutionary war that deposed the dictatorship of <PERSON> Anastasio </PERSON> <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON>. The Sandinistas and the Contras negotiated a truce in March and agreed to discuss a permanent end to their 7-year-old civil war. But a series of high-level talks collapsed without agreement on June 9. In recent weeks there has been a sharp increase in the number of Contra attacks reported by the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. At least eight civilians and several doze