<HEAD>Government Bans Mandela Birthday Concert</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government banned a birthday concert for <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> because it is terrified of any event that honors the jailed black leader, anti-apartheid activists said. Activists had hoped to the pop music show would be the highlight of celebrations marking <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>'s 70th birthday. But <PERSON> Aubrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Mokoena </PERSON>, an activist who coordinated arrangements for the `` Concert for Peace,'' said the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> told organizers Thursday that the show would be scrapped. The day-long concert was to feature some of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s top black musicians and take place near the black township of <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION>. It was scheduled for Sunday, the day before <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>'s birthday. <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> is probably the most popular leader among <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s disenfranchised black majority <PERSON> Mokoena </PERSON> said the government declined to give reasons for the ban. `` The only possible conclusion is that the South African government is terrified of the concept of the Mandela celebration,'' <PERSON> Mokoena </PERSON> said. The organizers had anticipated a crowd of 25,000 people at the concert and planned to donate the proceeds to charities. They had arranged to hire a private security firm to ensure that no disturbances occurred. Police last week arrested several people organizing a separate Mandela birthday celebration in <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>. Activists fear that event will also be banned, but the government has made no announcement. Activists said at a news conference after the arrests that they were determined to find a way to honor <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>. `` In spite of all the intimidation, in spite of the obvious fear of the government, our decision is clear: we wi