<HEAD>Sugar Making Comeback Relative To Other Sweeteners</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sugar is making a comeback among American consumers after years of trailing other sweeteners and might be about ready to hold its own, says an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> analyst. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said that in 1987 Americans used more sugar, instead of less, for the first time in 12 years. Per capita consumption rose 3 pecent to an average of 62.2 pounds for the year. The deliveries of refined sugar to the food and beverage industries, and wholesale and retail markets, rose 5 percent from 1986 to more than 7.6 million tons. Despite the increase, sugar still made up only about 40 percent of the 152.4 pounds average 1987 per capita consumption of all sweeteners, including those with calories and those without. <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> said in the July issue of Farmline magazine that growth in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> population and higher incomes have contributed to greater sugar use. But there are other reasons, and one of the most important involves <ORGANIZATION> HFCS </ORGANIZATION>, or high fructose corn syrup. `` After more than a decade of seizing markets from sugar in such diverse products as beverages, baked goods, jams and other processed foods, the cheaper to produce <ORGANIZATION> HFCS </ORGANIZATION> has come close to reaching its technical limit of substitutability,'' he said. `` This has stanched the dramatic losses of sugar in the past 12 years.'' <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> added: `` Of course, there is the possibility of a technical breakthrough -LRB- such as -RRB- lower-cost forms of dry fructose or low-calorie sweeteners.'' The sugar industry had been threatened by rival sweeteners for many years but suffered no major losses until about 1975 when <ORGANIZATION> HFCS </ORGANIZATION> emerged. Sugar prices were high at the time, and <ORGANIZATION> HFCS </ORGANIZATION> was cheaper to produce, an advantage it still holds. At the time, in 1975, the beverage industry was sugar's largest single market, using 25 percent of the sugar available. By last year beverages used only 3 percent, turning to <ORGANIZATION> HFCS </ORGANIZATION> and non-caloric sweeteners for diet drinks. Sugar deliveries to the beverage industry dropped to 212,000 tons in 1987 from 2 million in 1975. But in other industrial uses, sugar and <ORGANIZATION> HFCS </ORGANIZATION> are not always interchangeable, <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> said. For example, sugar deliveries to bakery and cereal manufacturers rose to 1.5 million tons last year from 1.2 million in 1975. Candy makers increased sugar use last year by 9.1 percent from 1986. One reason is that <ORGANIZATION> HFCS </ORGANIZATION>, a liquid, is less adaptable in candy manufacture. A big question for the future of <ORGANIZATION> HFCS </ORGANIZATION> involves federal sugar policy. <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> said that much will depend on whether sugar will continue to be supported by the government at current price levels, which encourage the development of substitute sweeteners. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sugar policy also involves imports and measures used to protect domestic producers from cheaper foreign sugar flooding the market. Although there was some strengthening, in May the world price of sugar was still only 9 cents per pound, or only half of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> support price. Bills are in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> which would lower the support levels, thereby reducing domestic output and boosting imports. That is the approach favored by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. `` Another initiative by the administration seeks to liberalize trade through multilateral trade negotiations of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-,'' he said. `` The goal is to eliminate trade-distorting subsidies and allow better market access for sugar worldwide.'' <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> said a freer world market could reduce sugar prices for American consumers but would probably also reduce the size of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sugar industry.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> are the first states to be officially designated by the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> as a natural disaster areas because of this year's drought, but others are in line. The designation opens the way for farmers in the designated areas to apply for <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> emergency loans. The Missouri designation was announced Wednesday by Gov. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashcroft </PERSON> and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Oxley </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ohio </LOCATION>, who also announced the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> designation. <PERSON> Oxley </PERSON> said 92 percent to 100 percent of <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>'s corn crop will be lost because of the drought, according to federal estimates. According to <ORGANIZATION> FmHA </ORGANIZATION> officials, 514 counties in <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> and at least 13 other states have been logged for official designation. As of Thursday, those included: <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Other states also have submitted requests, too, the agency said, including one from Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinner </PERSON> who asked that all of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> be designated. Those, however, had not yet been registered by <ORGANIZATION> FmHA </ORGANIZATION>, a spokesman said. In his letter to <PERSON> Ashcroft </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> request was based on drought damages `` Jan. 1, 1988, through June 24, 1988, and continuing.'' <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> said that to be eligible for <ORGANIZATION> FmHA </ORGANIZATION> emergency loans farmers `` must have multi-peril or federal crop insurance, if available, to offset any losses sustained in crops'' planted after Jan. 1, 1987, as required by the 1985 farm law. A total of 2,007 counties in 38 states also have been designated for emergency drought hay and feed assistance through another <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> agency, the <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stabilization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>.
