<HEAD>Opposition Presses Protests; Salinas Urges Unity, Change in Shaken
PRI</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Opposition candidates began a nationwide round of rallies to press their charges that the governing party stole the presidential election. The victor, <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON>, said the governing <ORGANIZATION> Institutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> must respond to calls for change after its biggest losses ever in the July 6 balloting. An estimated 15,000 supporters of conservative <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> candidate <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Clouthier </PERSON> withstood a downpour Thursday in the western city of <LOCATION> Guadalajara </LOCATION> to hear him accuse the government of manipulating the election. He said his appearance in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s second largest city was the first in a national tour to gather signatures in a referendum to decide whether the party should seek to have the election annulled. <PERSON> Clouthier </PERSON>, who won in <LOCATION> Guadalajara </LOCATION> but finished third nationwide in results announced Wednesday by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, said he does not know who won. But he said neither <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> nor <PERSON> Cuauhtemoc </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON>, candidate of the left, can claim a credible victory. The commission, dominated by the <ORGANIZATION> Institutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, or <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> won with 50.36 percent of the vote. <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON> followed with 31.12 percent and <PERSON> Clouthier </PERSON> with 17.07 percent. <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON>, candidate of the leftist <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Mexican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, planned to begin a national tour next week after a major rally in the huge Zocalo Plaza on Saturday. He said he would target regions where he considers `` fraud was the most brutal and ran roughshod on our party members.'' The son of one of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s most popular presidents, <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON> led a dissident movement in the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> before breaking away to become candidate of several small parties. Commission figures showed he won in the Federal District, the adjacent states of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Morelos </LOCATION>, the central western state of <LOCATION> Michoacan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Baja </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, the northern half of the peninsula. The loss was the biggest ever since the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> was founded in 1929, but it still retained control of both houses of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Parties supporting <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON> won four of the 64 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> seats in an unprecedented loss for the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION>. Both the left and the right made inroads in the <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION>, the lower house of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The absence of any official presidential returns for a week after the balloting fed reports of fraud and rumors of feuding between old-guard <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> leaders who wanted their traditional overwhelming victories and supporters of <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON>, who said he wanted a clean election. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON>, receiving congratulatory visits from party-affiliated organizations Thursday, said he had been given `` a clear mandate for change'' and called for unity among all parties and factions. `` The <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> today has the capacity and flexibility to face successfully the call for change,'' he told state governors and the party's executive committee. `` May no one try to convert political plurality into national division.'' <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON>, academic coordinator at the prestigious <ORGANIZATION> Colegio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION>, said that since Mexican independence, elections have been used to transfer power within a group or party rather than to decide which would govern or who the leaders would be. `` It is because of this tremendous weight of anti-democratic history that what is happening today is important and it is for that same reason that the change in electoral custom _ from non-competitive elections to true elections _ finds so many obstacles,'' he wrote in the newspaper Excelsior this week. Change, he said, is only beginning. `` It's obvious that the birth of modern <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> is turning out to be a difficult and prolonged delivery and that it's still not known if it will reach a happy ending,'' he said. Some of the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION>'s losing candidates said the party must reform to survive. `` With the triumphs obtained by the opposition a profound restructuring ... of the party to recover the ground lost in the past elections becomes indispensable,'' <PERSON> Cuauhtemoc </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrales </PERSON> told the newspaper <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Toluca </LOCATION>, 40 miles west of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> in the state of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. He lost a congressional election in the <LOCATION> Toluca-Metepec </LOCATI