<FIRST>r a PM-AlohaHearing     07-15 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Aloha Hearing,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>FAA Expert: Better Inspections Key To Avoiding Repeat Of Aloha
Accident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Proper aircraft inspection is the `` weak link'' in efforts to prevent accidents like the one that ripped the top off an <ORGANIZATION> Aloha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> jetliner at 24,000 feet, a <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> expert says. A <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> panel, which winds up four days of testimony here today, is trying to determine the cause of the April 28 accident and what it can teach about the problems of operating aging airplanes. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Swift </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> national resource specialist on aircraft structures from <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, also told the hearing Thursday that he believes the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737 broke open because a bonded fuselage joint separated, leading to a rapid failure of the metal along a line of rivets. `` It was the worst-case condition,'' <PERSON> Swift </PERSON> said. Another <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> witness told the inquiry board that tiny cracks were found in nearly half the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737 jetliners known to have been inspected under an <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> airworthiness directive issued after the <LOCATION> Aloha </LOCATION> accident. An 18-foot section blew away from the top of the pressurized <ORGANIZATION> Aloha </ORGANIZATION> jet over <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, throwing a flight attendant to her death and injuring 61 of the 94 people aboard. Passengers in the forward cabin were exposed to the air while the pilot made an emergency landing. Asked by inquiry chairman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lauber </PERSON> what `` the bottom line'' was for preventing another such accident, <PERSON> Swift </PERSON> replied it rested with the airlines and their inspection programs for corrosion and metal fatigue. `` I know where the weak link is, and it's in the inspection,'' <PERSON> Swift </PERSON> said. Such inspections are mind-numbing jobs, he said, adding that research was needed to take the `` human element'' out of the inspections. `` Hell, we put a man on the moon, why ca n't we develop an inspection program that can guarantee we can find these cracks?'' he asked. The Aloha jet, built in 1969, had had 89,680 landings, second-highest of any 737. Swift, one of the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> officials who examined the jet, said he believes adhesive gave way along a lap joint where parts of the fuselage are bonded and riveted together, most likely because of corrosion. Within a week of the <LOCATION> Aloha </LOCATION> accident, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> ordered all 737s with 30,000 or more landings to undergo a special visual inspection of fuselage lap joints, and 737s with more than 50,000 landings to have additional inspections using high-frequency electronic equipment. Airlines were required to fix any problems found and report test results to the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, manager of the airframe branch in the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> aircraft certification office, told the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> panel 291 planes were affected by the order As of this week, he said, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> has received reports on 100 planes, of which 49 had cracks. Five or more cracks were found in 14 of those planes, he said. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashworth </PERSON>, manager of the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> aircraft certification division, said he was concerned about the cracks but saw no imminent danger to the planes or to air passengers. `` We of course are requiring that all cracks we find be repaired. That's only prudent maintenance,'' he said.
