<HEAD>Nation's First Liver-Pancreas Transplant Performed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first person to undergo a liver-pancreas transplant in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is making steady progress and appears to have been cured of his insulin-dependent diabetes, his doctors say. `` He can go to the ice cream parlor now and nothing will happen to him,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Andreas </PERSON> <PERSON> Tzakis </PERSON>, one of about 10 surgeons who took part in the landmark operation. The 39-year-old <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> man, whose identity was withheld at his request, received the organs during 16 hours of surgery July 1 at <LOCATION> Presbyterian-University </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>. In addition to being diabetic since 1969, the man had hepatitis, an inflammation of the liver, which he got from blood transfusions during a 1964 heart operation. The diabetes, unrelated to the hepatitis, struck him when he was 20. The man eventually would have died from his condition. `` Both he and his wife ... are a very strong couple. Psychologically, he's doing very good,'' <PERSON> Tzakis </PERSON> said at a news conference Thursday. The man could have been saved with a new liver alone, but doctors worried the single organ might have failed without a new pancreas to overcome the diabetes. The pancreas, a pear-shaped organ behind the stomach, produces insulin, a hormone needed to convert sugar, starches and other food into energy. Severe diabetes prevents the body from producing or properly using insulin, making daily injections necessary. Complications include kidney and heart disease, blindness, nerve damage and gangrene leading to amputation. <PERSON> Tzakis </PERSON>' patient had experienced only mild nerve damage and eye problems, which studies show can sometimes be reversed. `` Our patient was an ideal candidate for this operation because he unfortunately suffered from both diabetes and hepatitis, had the proper motivation to undergo a complicated procedure and understood the risk,'' <PERSON> Tzakis </PERSON> said. The operation had been performed only twice before, both times in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, according to <PERSON> Tzakis </PERSON>. The patient was in serious condition Thursday, considered normal, with the main threats being organ rejection or infection, <PERSON> Tzakis </PERSON> said. He could be discharged in a month or so and remain near the hospital for another few weeks before returning home. Two other diabetics currently are awaiting liver-pancreas transplants in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>, according to <PERSON> Tzakis </PERSON>.
