<HEAD>China Calls for Communists and Nationalists to Join Hands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s leading daily said today the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> regards the <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> on <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> as its counterpart and expressed disappointment that a recent <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> congress </ORGANIZATION> did not end a ban on contacts with the mainland. The People's Daily, the official voice of the party, said in a front-page editorial that the two parties have `` unshirkable duties'' to carry forth the great traditions of the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> people. `` What we can contribute to the future of our nation and mankind is unlimited. We hope that the two parties can rid themselves of past differences and unite hand-in-hand to achieve the cause that was left unfinished by our ancestors.'' The Communist and Nationalist parties formed common fronts in the 1920s and 1930s to fight Chinese warlords and the invading Japanese, but fought a civil war following the end of World War II that ended in the flight of <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Kai-shek </PERSON>'s Nationalists to <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> in 1949. The editorial said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> `` highly appreciated'' the 13th <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for dismissing the idea of an independent <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> and calling for efforts to attain the historic task of reunification. `` We believe that the trend of relaxing tensions will develop after the conclusion of the 13th Party Congress. This is what the people of the two sides expect,'' it said. But the daily expressed disappointment that the Nationalists made no change in their policies of regarding the Communists as enemies and maintaining the `` three nos'' policy of no contact, no negotiations and no compromise with the mainland. `` This is really against the times and will of the people,'' it said. The Nationalists, while saying the ban on official contacts will stay, did approve a plan to ease the ban on visits to <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> by mainland Chinese residents, allow import of raw materials from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and permit <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> business investment on the mainland if it is conducted through a third country. Last year the <LOCATION> Taipei </LOCATION> government removed restrictions on visits to the mainland by <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> residents. Tens of thousands of tourists, businessmen and people visiting family have since traveled to the mainland. The editorial also said the Nationalists are unreasonable in their statements that the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the people of the mainland should be separated. The <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, it said, has become one with the people of the mainland. The daily said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> continues to welcome people from <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> for visits and business and expressed confidence that the policy of `` one country, two systems'' can help reunify the nation. Under that system, <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> is to retain its capitalist system for 50 years after <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> returns the colony to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in 1997.
