<HEAD>Government Officials Ban Coca Farms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government said it will approve a new anti-cocaine law that will ban most coca plantations and impose tougher sentences on drug dealers and corrupt officials. The law is the first ban in <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION> on cultivation of the coca leaf, which is used to produce cocaine. The measure was approved by the lower house of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last week and by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday. President <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Paz </PERSON> <PERSON> Estenssoro </PERSON> said he will sign the law when it reaches his desk. The law limits coca plant cultivation to 29,652 acres and bans production on 76,601 acres. Farmers will receive $ 2,000 for every hectare of coca plants they destroy, with $ 365 of that amount provided by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which has long pressured <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION> to crack down on its cocaine trade. The law also toughens penalties against drug traffickers, coca leaf producers and public officials who take bribes from drug dealers or who interfere with the prosecution of traffickers. `` Over the next five years if the government can get international backing, cocaine trafficking as it is known in <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION> can be seriously interrupted,'' said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Mocolini </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> office in <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paz </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s poorest country, produces an estimated one-third of the cocaine that reaches <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and European markets. Last week, thousands of coca leaf farmers attacked a police and <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> camp in the <LOCATION> Chapare </LOCATION> coca-leaf producing region. Poli