<HEAD>Conference Debates How Christianity Let Holocaust Happen</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with resumption of conference,
remarks from Reagan, Kohl; picks up 10th pvs: This crime...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Clergymen, scholars and survivors of the Holocaust today applauded a message from West German Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> acknowledging his nation's responsibility for the <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> genocide. `` Germans became guilty of that crime as individuals, but they are collectively liable for the injustice committed in their name,'' said <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>'s message, read to 500 people attending `` Remembering for the Future,'' a conference on the Holocaust and its impact on modern generations. <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> joined President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, French President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, Israeli President <PERSON> Chaim </PERSON> <PERSON> Herzog </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> head <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Delors </PERSON> in sending messages to the conference on its final day. The West German leader's words were read by <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON>, the Czech-born Jewish publisher who sponsored the weeklong conference. <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON> lauded <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s willingness to face its past, and at his request, <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> was given a round of applause. `` No one can rule out the possibility of comparable atrocities happening again,'' said <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>'s message. `` It must not be forgotten. It is an appeal to each one of us to examine our own thoughts over and over again.'' It said: `` We Germans are prepared to live with this terrible truth.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s message said the world `` can never have reminders enough about the tragedy that results when nations abandon their reverence for the sanctity of every human life.'' More than 500 scholars, concentration camp survivors, theologians, artists and teachers met here to examine how Christianity could have allowed the Holocaust to happen. `` The words ` never again' must ever be the pledge of all who pause in remembrance of those who have perished and of all who cherish mankind's deepest hopes and ideals,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said in his message. The conference, which began in <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION> a week ago, concludes with leaders of Christian churches joining in prayers for the 6 million Jewish victims of <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s genocide during World War II. <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> professor <PERSON> Elie </PERSON> <PERSON> Wiesel </PERSON>, a Nobel prize-winning author and survivor of the <LOCATION> Buchenwald </LOCATION> concentration camp where 10,000 people died daily, said that after a lifetime of studying and writing about the Holocaust, he still could not understand how it happened. `` Often I think of the children walking slowly, quietly, obediently, to the flames or to the mass graves, and I am almost grateful for the pain that links my memory to theirs,'' he said in a keynote address. The conference ranked among the biggest of its kind held outside the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, where there has been an expansion in academic studies of the Holocaust. <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON>, 65, lost most of his family at the hands of the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> in World War II. `` This crime, this disaster, has been examined mainly in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON> said Thursday. `` Yet it was in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> that it happened.'' <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON>'s wife <PERSON> Elisabeth </PERSON>, a French Protestant, was the main organizer of the conference. As a child she lived in a largely Jewish district of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> from which most her friends vanished as the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> rounded up the Jews. She has long believed that Christianity contained a strong streak of anti-Semitism. The Jewish Chronicle, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s top Jewish newspaper, has predicted that the conference `` could radically affect the way British people and institutions think'' about the Holocaust. <PERSON> Herzog </PERSON>, in his message, said he hoped the meeting would `` help to shape a future in which the horror will never be forgotten.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> said it was important for generations who did not live through `` those agonized years'' to learn how and why it happened. `` That knowledge will help people everywhere who are determined that nothing like this shall ever happen again,'' she added in her message to the conference. Organizers timed the meeting just before next week's Lambeth conference, an international gathering of Anglican bishops. Mrs. <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON> said the archbishop of <ORGANIZATION> Canterbury </ORGANIZATION>, the Most Rev. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Runcie </PERSON>, pledged that the prelates will discuss the outcome of `` Remembering for the Future.'' Leading participants included American academic specialists on Jewish-Chr, <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Eckardt </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Alice </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Eckardt </PERSON>; Holocaust historian <PERSON> Yehuda </PERSON> <PERSON> Bauer </PERSON> and the Rev. <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> Littell </PERSON>, an American Methodist minister who helped pioneer Holocaust studies in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. In associated events, organizistian relationsers have arranged a <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> exhibition of drawings produced by Jews in concentration camps and a concert at the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opera </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> featuring works by composers <PERSON> Dmitri </PERSON> <PERSON> Shostakovich </PERSON>, <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Britten </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gustav </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahler </PERSON>.
