<HEAD>Last North American Volkswagen Rolls Off Line</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW STANTON, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The last <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> made in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> has rolled off the assembly line, but it's not for sale. `` The car will remain with the company. It will be a permanent fixture at <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON>, spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the West German automaker's <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> subsidiary. The white, two-door 1989 Golf model was completed Thursday afternoon at the plant, the first foreign-owned automobile assembly plant in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Its final resting place has yet to be determined, <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON> said, but officials are considering a corporate museum in <LOCATION> Wolfsburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, which has about 100 cars. There was no fanfare as the car, the 1,197,411 th vehicle built at the plant, rolled off the production line Photographers and TV cameras were not allowed to record the event. The plant, which produced its first car in 1978, is about 35 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>. Dogged by faltering sales of its American-built cars, <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> announced in November it would cut its losses by serving the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market with vehicles built in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. About 2,500 people eventually will lose their jobs because of the shutdown.
