<TEXT>
 A two-engine plane crashed in a jungle in southern <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> and killed 10 of the 11 people on board, authorities said today. A 5-year-old boy survived, they said. The boy, <PERSON> Remy </PERSON> <PERSON> Revilla </PERSON>, suffered serious burns and was hospitalized in critical condition in <LOCATION> Ciudad </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bolivar </LOCATION>, civil aeronautics officials said. <LOCATION> Ciudad </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bolivar </LOCATION> is 280 miles east of the capital, <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION>. The boy's father was killed in the crash Thursday, the officials said. Rescue patrols sent to the area said most of the bodies were burned beyond recognition. The plane took off before noon from <ORGANIZATION> Ciudad </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bolivar </ORGANIZATION> and was headed to <LOCATION> Icabaru </LOCATION>, near the Brazilian border. Most of the passengers, including four musicians, were to attend a party in <LOCATION> Icabaru </LOCATION>. A few minutes after takeoff, the pilot reported failure in one of the engines. `` Nothing was heard since from the pilot,'' a civil aeronautics official said.
