Picks up 4th pvs, `The legislature...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Authorities in <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> are preventing vehicles carrying foodstuffs from reaching a breakaway region of their republic and have imposed an economic blockade on the mostly Armenian area, a local journalist said today. The official <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency blamed the supply problems on a strike in the disputed region, <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>. It said more than 130 railway cars loaded with supplies were sitting at the train station in <LOCATION> Stepenakert </LOCATION>, the region's main city. More than 300 containers with foodstuffs have not been unloaded, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. The journalist from the state broadcasting authority said an airliner was forced to turn back to neighboring <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> on Thursday after <LOCATION> Azerbaijani </LOCATION> authorities refused to let it land in <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>. `` There are no more fruits or vegetables in our shops,'' the journalist said in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION>. `` We have almost no economic ties now with <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>.'' The legislature of <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>, an enclave the size of <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> whose 160,000 inhabitants are mostly Armenian, voted Tuesday to secede and join <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. The Azerbaijani government called the vote illegal and declared it void. `` We are under a virtual economic blockade,'' said the journalist, who spoke on condition of anonymity. `` The Azerbaijanis are trying to morally kill our movement, to strike down our just demands.'' For the past two months, <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> has been disrupted by strikes by ethnic Armenians who want to be united with the Armenian republic. <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> followed suit with strikes on July 4 demanding the annexation. The official <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency reported that the situation in <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION> remained tense. A general strike in the city continued. The journalist said none of the city's 20 factories was working and that bus service between <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION> and the Armenian cities of <LOCATION> Kirovakan </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Kafan </PERSON> was suspended. Buses to <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>, however, were setting out every other day with an escort of police brought in from the <LOCATION> Stavropol </LOCATION> region of southern <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION>, he said. On Thursday, an Aeroflot airliner en route from <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION> was forced to turn back after <LOCATION> Azerbaijani </LOCATION> authorities refused to let it land in <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION>, the journalist said. The airliner touched down in the Armenian city of <LOCATION> Goris </LOCATION>, and passengers returned to <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> by bus, he said. The journalist said `` several thousand'' troops were patrolling <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> today but that the area was quiet. A resident of <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION> said Thursday the ethnic dispute had taken a heavy toll. `` Our situation is very bad because the strike is continuing. No one is working,'' said the woman, who hung up the phone before giving her name. She said <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> residents had to rely on food produced locally. `` We are n't receiving food from <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>,'' she said, but `` we get some potatoes from the <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION> area.'' Activists said more than 150,000 people held a rally Thursday in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> urging <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>'s 10 deputies to the Soviet parliament to press for annexation of <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>. About three-fourths of the enclave's residents are ethnic Armenians, most of them Christians, but the region was assigned to predominately Moslem <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> in 1923. Armenians believe the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, the highest legislative body in the Soviet government, will meet Monday to consider the <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> question. In <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> on Thursday, <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Vadim </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Perfilyev </PERSON> said such a meeting was likely but that he did n't know when it would occur. <PERSON> Khovik </PERSON> <PERSON> Vasilyan </PERSON>, an Armenian activist, said by telephone from <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> today that most of the Armenian capital's factories were still strikebound but that transport was functioning normally in the city of 1.1 million people. He said another rally in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> to press Armenian demands for annexation was planned Saturday. Pravda, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> daily, said Thursday the work stoppage in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> had cost $ 65 million in lost production and that $ 29 million worth of construction had not been completed. Thirty-two people were killed in ethnic riots in February at <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>, 26 of them Armenians. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said that about 20,000 Azerbajanis living in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> had fled to <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> and that as of Wednesday, 7,265 Armenians who once lived in <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION> and other <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> cities had returned to <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>.
