<BYLINE>By NABILA MEGALLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Iranian gunboats struck a Liberian-registered tanker in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> today and returned twice more to attack it after the captain called for help from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warships, gulf-based shipping executives said. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> missile frigate <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> responded to the distress signal but did not confront the raiders, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said. The shipping executives identified the targeted vessel as the 85,989-ton Sea Victory, operated by the <LOCATION> Piraeus </LOCATION>, Greece-based <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navigation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. They said the captain put out his distress signal at about 2 p.m. and gave his location as five miles south of <LOCATION> Farsi </LOCATION> island. The captain said the attack was carried out by two Iranian gunboats. He was heard frantically shouting, `` American warship! Americans warship!'' and within minutes he reported that the gunboats were `` returning to attack,'' said the executives who monitored the radio calls. The captain was still shouting for help when the gunboats returned a third time to raid the vessel, said the executives. They said the attacks occurred within about 15 minutes. The attacks caused a fire, which the crew extinguished. In a radio telephone contact after the Iranians turned back, the captain was overheard by monitors as saying the Iranians attacked three times, and he described the condition of his ship as covered with `` lots of holes.'' He was overheard saying `` no casualties, thank God,'' but he also said that his second officer suffered minor injuries. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement that the tanker issued a call for help but was able to steam west under its own power. When it reached international wat