<TEXT>
 A sailor convicted of murdering and robbing a payroll officer aboard a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> destroyer was spared the death penalty and given life imprisonment after proclaiming his innocence. Petty Officer 1st Class <PERSON> Ruben </PERSON> <PERSON> Colon </PERSON> was sentenced Thursday by a five-member court-martial panel. He was convicted Wednesday of killing Lt. j.g. <PERSON> Ratish </PERSON> <PERSON> Prasad </PERSON> aboard the USS Hancock at dock here March 15 and stealing $ 94,000 from the ship's safe. Colon, who had a 14-year military career as a <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> military policeman and <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> electronic warfare technician, faced the death penalty because he was found guilty of murder while committing a robbery. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has not executed one of its members since 1849. The sentence came after 34-year-old Colon, who did not testify at his four-day court-martial, read a statement urging panel members to reconsider the verdict. `` There was no one more surprised at your findings than myself,'' <PERSON> Colon </PERSON> said. `` I was surprised for the simple fact that I did n't do it.'' Colon, of <LOCATION> Vega </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Baja </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, pointed out loose ends in the investigation such as several other suspects who failed polygraph examinations when questioned about the killing and theft. Colon was charged with taking more than $ 94,000 and 2,575 blank <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Treasury checks. He was arrested April 12 after investigators found more than $ 87,000 and the checks in a safe-deposit box rented in his name. `` If you are all convinced Petty Officer Colon is the perpetrator, death is not appropriate,'' defense attorney Lt. <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> Michels </PERSON> argued. `` Make Petty Officer Colon live with it the rest of his natural life. Make him live with the horror and the 