<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> today applauded overwhelming <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> votes condemning Sandinista leaders for human rights abuses and urged <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to approve swiftly further aid for <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s Contra rebels. White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>, speaking for the president, said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> `` is pleased with the overwhelming, bipartisan votes'' on the issue. `` These votes send the message to the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is firmly committed to the achievement of freedom and democracy in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. `` The Sandinistas' conduct makes clear that they will not institute democratic reform and cease their threats to the security of <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> unless effectively pressured and persuaded to do so,'' the spokesman said. `` To achieve democracy in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and security for all of <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> clearly requires a viable and effective Nicaraguan Democratic Resistance,'' he said. `` When the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> returns, the president hopes they will move swifly to enact legislation currently being formulated in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> for further aid to the resistance,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> voted 385-18 on Thursday to condemn <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s leftist Sandinista government for `` brutal suppression of basic human rights. It urged the democracies of <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> to meet to assess the situation. The House action followed closely on the 91-4 roll call by which the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday night adopted a stronger resolution warning that military aid to the Contras could be approved if the Sandinista government continues to frustrate democratic reforms and does not end human rights abuses. Both resolutions condemn the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> for breaking up a recent peaceful demonstration, jailing more than 40 people, including opposition leaders, closing down the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> radio station and expelling <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Melton </PERSON> and eight other American diplomats. Military aid was ended last February, but a $ 47.1 million aid package containing $ 20 million for military purposes was introduced late Wednesday in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> by Minority Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, R-Kan. The White House on Thursday expressed support for the combined humanitarian and military aid, which would last through next March. Under the measure, aid to the Contras would be authorized only after the president certifies that it is necessary and after both houses of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> approve it. White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said Thursday that the White House was working with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on a new Contra aid bill and said <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> has been `` very helpful'' in this effort. When <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was asked Wednesday whether he was supporting efforts o get a new Contra aid package through <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, he responded, `` You bet I am.'' Advocates of ending military assistance contended the step would encourage the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> and Contras to negotiate seriously and to cooperate in the Central American peace process fostered by Costa Rican President <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Arias </PERSON>. American humanitarian assistance to the Contra forces has continued. Until the Sandinista crackdown last weekend there had appeared to be virtually no prospect that military aid to the Contras would be restored. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> appeared divided on the issue on Thursday. `` I expect this body to take stronger action later,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lagomarsino </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Calif </LOCATION>, echoing many of his colleagues. `` This resolution contains strong words; but it is just that _ strong words,'' he said. `` There are no teeth in this resolution.'' But Rep. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonior </PERSON>, D-Mich., also speaking for many of his colleagues, said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should do nothing to fuel further fighting in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> <PERSON> Bonior </PERSON> said that while it is important to `` condemn any violations of the principle of democracy,'' he believes there is still life in the peace process. `` The basis for progress, I believe, still remains,'' he said. In Senate testimony, Ambassador <PERSON> Melton </PERSON> said he believes congressional resolutions do little to sway the Sandinistas. <PERSON> Melton </PERSON> said he does think `` the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> are impressed with any evidence of resoluteness on the part of the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and evidence of bipartisan resolve.'' But he added, `` I think the Sandinistas are impressed more by actions than by words.''
