ry notes. The financial scandal, <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s biggest since World War II, was uncovered in August. Only 8,500 of the company's 13,000 workforce are still on the payroll. Workers throughout <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> are experiencing hardship as the government implements an austerity program designed to reduce 175 percent inflation and limit the $ 21 billion foreign debt. On July 6, thousands of workers from <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s largest rubber and shoe plant broke into the parliament building to press demands for higher pay.
