<HEAD>Paul Tsongas Is Alive and Well, Living As Former Senator in
Hometown</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOWELL, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 There is one well-known Democratic politician of Greek ancestry from <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> who is not seeking the presidency and is n't even going to the Democratic convention in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. `` I have no political ambitions, whatsoever,'' says former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Tsongas </PERSON>, once hailed as a liberal maverick on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>. `` We're much happier now than when I was in office.'' He has scaled down his aspirations since he disclosed that he had cancer and left the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> one month before his 43rd birthday. The last traces of cancer are gone, but he prefers the limelight of this old mill town to the spotlight of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Though no longer a senator, <PERSON> Tsongas </PERSON> still makes headlines in The Sun, a 55,000-circulation daily that serves his hometown. It has been reporting his doings ever since he sat on the <ORGANIZATION> Lowell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> in the late 1960s and right on through his election to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> in 1974, first Democrat to win the district in about 90 years, and to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in 1979. One recent edition landed on <PERSON> Tsongas </PERSON>' side porch carrying an article about his tangle over the ouster of the <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> school superintendent. He also created a statewide stir recently when, as the head of a study commission on the environment, he called for a building moratorium on <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cod </LOCATION>. The matter, which will be on the November ballot, is still being hotly debated. <PERSON> Tsongas </PERSON> enjoys watching his friend, Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, reach for the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, in particular because the likely Democratic presidential nominee expounds <PERSON> Tsongas </PERSON>' philosophy that the Democrats' survival depends on integrating the needs of business. `` Liberals have to be concerned with economics. Democrats have to be the friends of business. ... The major issue facing the country is the sense of decline, that we're going to be some latter-day <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>,'' he said. Although he once floated the idea of running for president, it's enough for <PERSON> Tsongas </PERSON> to stump for his friend to know he is n't missing a thing In some ways he prefers wielding influence as an ex-senator. `` I'm really struck by how much respect there is for the office of senator,'' he said. `` It is very special ... and you can use that. How many 47-year-old former senators do you know? `` Certainly in people's dealings with me, they are much more accepting of me now than when I was in office. I have no political ambitions, so I'm less tainted. Also, there's the illness issue.'' In September 1983 he was diagnosed as having non-Hodgkins lymphoma, a relatively mild cancer of the lymph nodes that attacks part of the immune system. Nearly four months later, in the middle of his second run for the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Tsongas </PERSON> decided it would be better for everyone if he took his wife, <PERSON> Nikki </PERSON>, and their three daughters home to <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON>. Since then he has undergone a bone marrow transplant and has been declared cancer-free. <PERSON> Tsongas </PERSON> works for a prestigious <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> law firm, <ORGANIZATION> Foley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hoag </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Eliot </PERSON>, making deals and serving on corporate boards and taking pro bono assignments. His latest battle, over his proposal that construction on the <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> be halted until the peninsula gets control of development, has led to abuse from builders and developers while filling his mailbox with letters from <PERSON> Cape </PERSON> <PERSON> Codders </PERSON> telling him to stick with it. `` I know I'm doing well because my political enemies are angry at me,'' he said, with glee, recalling the wrath of a roomful of developers at a public hearing on the issue. `` Six hundred people were shouting at me!'' He shrugged. ` I have nothing to fear, politically, and, with what I've been through ...'' `` The day I turn around and there's nobody behind me, is the day I get out of it. The mail I get is so passionate, you can not read that mail and say: ` I'm going to walk away.'''
