<HEAD>Former King Aide Young Now Convention City Mayor and Booster</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 He marched with <PERSON> King </PERSON>, won election as <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>'s first black congressman since Reconstruction and later championed human rights as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> Now <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> is <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'s mayor and chief booster, using the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> as a hometown showcase for the sales pitch he makes around the world. With 13,000 reporters in town or on the way, Young is scheduling daily news conferences in contrast to his usual practice of scheduling none. As a prominent black Democratic office-holder, he came under early pressure to endorse <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. But he steered clear, saying that as host mayor for the convention he should n't be taking such stands. `` I'd like to see <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> have a worldwide reputation as a market center,'' <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said in a recent interview. `` We've been trying to find ways to create jobs and to wipe out some of the problems of poverty in our city by actually attracting and generating new wealth.'' Young's emphasis on improving <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> with private investment has won enough support from white business leaders to have him thinking aloud about a run for governor next year on a platform of economic development. But the mayor also bears some bruises from charges he has forgotten the poor while courting the rich. `` I think he has been good for <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> as a whole, bringing in business, but I do n't think the low-income community looks at him as being good for them,'' said <PERSON> Louise </PERSON> <PERSON> Watley </PERSON>, president of the tenants' association in the Carver Homes housing project. <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said he