<SECOND>AM-Jackson-1972 Bjt,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jackson's '88 Delegates Recall '72 Convention Fight With Daley</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 What a difference 16 years can make. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, the solo remaining also-ran in the field of candidates for the Democratic presidential nomination, had to wage a bitter fight just to win a seat on the Democratic convention floor in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> in 1972. <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Jefferson </PERSON> remembers. One of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s allies at that time _ just as she is one of his delegates this time _ she was so pleased with the rebels' victory at that steamy convention that she took a plunge into a swimming pool with her clothes on. `` It was that kind of excitement,'' she says. `` It was a great day.'' The challenging bloc of four dozen renegade delegates faced contempt of court and jail for pursuing their fight. Even after they won, it took a 9-0 decision by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to nail down the victory. And the event may have played a role in the demise of the political operation led by then-Chicago Mayor <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, one of the most powerful big city political machines in the country. Mrs. <PERSON> Jefferson </PERSON>, 64, chief executive officer of the <ORGANIZATION> Midwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, a West Side group in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, is headed to the convention in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> with at least four other <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> delegates who were with <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and then-alderman <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON> in the rebel group in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. Here's how it happened: A week before the 1972 convention, the party's credentials committee, which leaned toward <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> McGovern </PERSON>, granted the Singer-Jackson delegates convention seats on a 71-61 vote. That decision was challenged on the first day of the convention, a session which lasted well into the next morning. The challenge failed in a floor vote. The memory still rankles <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyons </PERSON>, one of the ousted <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> delegates. `` It was one of the most monstrous things I've ever seen,'' said <PERSON> Lyons </PERSON>, 57, a former state senator. He said he and other delegates received thousands of votes, `` and we were replaced by ... people who met in somebody's living room. ... It was a theft.'' <PERSON> McGovern </PERSON>, the Democratic presidential nominee in 1972, had helped set the stage for the spectacle of keeping <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> from the convention floor. After the tumultuous 1968 Democratic National Convention in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, where anti-war demonstrators rocked the city and clashed with <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>'s city police force, <PERSON> McGovern </PERSON> chaired a commission that rewrote party rules to make room for more minorities, women and young people. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Cook </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, under <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>'s leadership, flagrantly violated every aspect of the rules,'' said <PERSON> Saul </PERSON> <PERSON> Mendelson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, a <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> delegate this year who was an alternate with the 1972 rebels The renegades held their own caucuses so they could offer an alternative. The anti-machine Democrats in the city knew that a simple protest would result in either a meaningless rebuke to the <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> forces on the convention floor, or expulsion of the 59 <LOCATION> Daley </LOCATION> people, leaving no representation for <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lyons </PERSON> saw the quickly called meetings as a political charade. Singer agrees that his delegates, chosen in church basements and living rooms, were not picked in orthodox ways. But `` I do n't think there was anyone in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> who did n't know what was going on,'' he said. After the credentials committee action, <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> forces went to court, and <LOCATION> Cook </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Circuit Judge <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Covelli </PERSON> prohibited the Singer-Jackson delegates from taking their convention seats. He threatened to jail leaders of the group if they disobeyed. Still, the rebels went to the convention, and faced a challenge on the floor. That vote `` shaped up as the most dramatic moment of the 1972 convention,'' according to `` Clout: Mayor <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> and his City,'' a 1975 book by <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> reporter and commentator <PERSON> Len </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>. `` The power of the old guard was under challenge.'' <PERSON> Mendelson </PERSON> said <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, who was keeping in touch with the delegation from his vacation home in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, would not agree to offers to split the delegate seats or take over leadership of the renegades himself. When the floor vote was taken, the Singer-Jackson group kept their seats. Critics said the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> rift would hurt <PERSON> McGovern </PERSON>'s chances. Maybe they did, but he lost 49 states, including <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, to <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> incumbent <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>. <PERSON> Covelli </PERSON>'s contempt-of-court order was stayed pending an appeal. The <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> later refused to hear the case, but the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled 9-0 for the Singer-Jackson group. The high court said that a political party has the right to make and enforce its own rules. That ended the threat of jail. Singer is n't convinced that the 1972 events led to the downfall of <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>'s machine. But Mrs. <PERSON> Jefferson </PERSON> thinks it was one step on the path of opening political power in the <LOCATION> Windy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> to those who had been shut out. `` I think it sort of ... changed the whole politics of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>,'' she said.
