<HEAD>Superconductivity Products For Sale Within 3 Years, Expert Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Products using superconductivity may appear on the market within three years, but it will take a decade or more for major applications of the technology, a prominent researcher said Friday. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chu </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION> commented in an interview after President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> awarded him and 19 other researchers the national medal of science. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> also awarded the national medal of technology to 10 prominent leaders in the technical industries. <PERSON> Chu </PERSON>, cited in the award description for a series of discoveries that helped raise the temperature of superconductive materials, said the new technology probably will be on the market in the form of special batteries and smoke detectors within two to three years. Microelectronics, electrical switches and other thin film electrical connectors will probably benefit from superconductivity within five years, <PERSON> Chu </PERSON> said. `` But any large scale application is at least 10 years away,'' he said. He predicted that by the end of the century superconductivity technology will be applied to the transmission of electricty and in large magnets. Superconductivity is a material state that permits electricity to flow without resistance. For decades, this was thought to occur only in metals chilled to temperatures approaching absolute zero: minus 459.6 degrees Fahrenheit. But <PERSON> Chu </PERSON> and other researchers, experimenting with ceramic compounds, have discovered how to raise the minimum superconductivity temperature to about inus 243 degrees, a temperature easily maintained with relatively inexpensive liquid nitrogen. Experts believe the technology will permit the manufacture of large, powerful magnets that could be used in transportation and medicine. The technology also could substantially reduce the cost of electricity since about half of generated power is lost to transmission resistance. Also, superconductivity could speed up computers and permit the more efficient storage of electricity. <PERSON> Chu </PERSON> said many nations now are racing to develop superconductivity technology and it is not clear who has the lead. He said he could not predict which nation would make the first practical application of the new technology, but `` I am very impressed by the Japanese effort.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, in presenting the medals, said it is vital that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> continue to promote research into emerging technologies that will have a major influence on life in the future. The president praised the medal winners as the `` men and women who are leading us into the new age of technology'' and that one of the most important jobs of government is `` knocking down the barriers of progress.'' `` <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s greatest resource is not the land,'' he said. `` No, <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s greatest resource is the genius of our people.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> gave 20 researchers the national medal of science, an honor established by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1959 to recognize achievements in physical, biological, mathematical, behavioral, social or engineering sciences. In addition to Chu, those receiving the science medal were <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldstein </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>; <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Murray </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Konrad </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>.; <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bromley </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Haven </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Stanford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Elias </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Corey </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Drucker </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Gainesville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gomory </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Armonk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Willis </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Calabasas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hilleman </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Merck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Point </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> 