<HEAD>Tass: Afghan Rebel Rockets Kill 20 In Kabul</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Afghan rebels fired more than 20 rockets into residential areas of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> on Friday, killing 20 people, wounding 34 and damaging a mosque and other buildings in the <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> capital, the <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency reported. The 5:30 a.m. attack, which <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> denounced as `` barbarous'' and a `` crime,'' was the latest reported on a major population center in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. Fighting has spread throughout the rugged and mountainous country as the Soviets withdraw their troops. Radio <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> also reported the attack on residential areas of the Afghan capital. The dispatch was monitored in <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. However, Afghan guerrilla leader <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Haq </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION> the insurgents do not target residential neighborhoods. He said the 15 to 20 rebel targets in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, which include the airport and Soviet Embassy, are not residential areas. <PERSON> Haq </PERSON> claimed Afghan government troops and their Soviet backers fire rockets into <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>'s residential districts to discredit the guerrillas and undermine their burgeoning popular support. `` We fire five rockets, and suddenly, we see 20 hit,'' <PERSON> Haq </PERSON> said, disavowing responsibility for all bombardments in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said it was `` monstrous'' to suggest Soviet forces would fire on a city they still occupied and said one of the 21 rockets launched on four <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> neighborhoods Friday exploded next to the Soviet Embassy. A label on one undetonated missile showed it came from <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. Afghan President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>, speaking to members of the armed forces, said Wednesday the insurgents have become bolder as Soviet troops depart. Under an accord signed April 14 in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> committed itself to begin withdrawing its more than 100,000 troops on May 15, and to complete the pullout by Feb. 15. Half of the Soviet soldiers are to be home by August. `` More than 35,000 Soviet internationalists have returned to their country,'' <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> said in a speech broadcast by official <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> radio and monitored by the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. However, <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> said: `` Armed interference in the internal affairs of our country ... is not only continuing, but has intensified. ... The extremists engage in savage crimes against peaceful people.'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said villages in the provinces of <LOCATION> Paktia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Paktika </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kunar </LOCATION> were heavily bombarded by the insurgents Thursday and that at least five people, including three children, were killed. Radio <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> said a land mine planted by guerrillas exploded Thursday in a crowded bazaar in <LOCATION> Rodat </LOCATION>, 30 miles from the border with <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. Two people were killed and one injured. More than 150 civilians were reported killed last weekend when the anti-Marxist rebels, aided by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, used artillery and rockets to shell populated areas in more than eight provinces. On July 8, a car packed with explosives blew up near a downtown movie theater in the eastern city of <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION>, killing 31 people and injuring 33 others, Soviet and Afghan media said. The Soviet withdrawal places the burden of warfare on the Afghan army, a force many Western observers believe will be unable to withstand the guerrillas. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>, however, said Afghan troops had staged several `` successful operations'' against the rebels recently. It said the army wiped out an insurgent detachment of more than 20 fighters and captured three people who planned to commit `` terrorist acts'' near the southern city of <LOCATION> Kandahar </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s official <ORGANIZATION> Bakhtar </ORGANIZATION> news agency reported that about 100 anti-government guerrillas were killed in the past week and that large quantities of weapons were seized, including rocket launchers, mortars, machine guns, grenade launchers and three U.S.-made Stinger missiles, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. Soviet and Afghan officials maintain they are abiding by the U.N.-brokered accords on <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. They have used increasingly tough language in accusing <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, which is also a signatory, of blatant violations. In particular, the Soviets say <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> is allowing its territory to be used to supply the rebels with weapons and ammunition and as the home of a rival Afghan government. State-run Radio <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> accused <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> on Friday of `` crude violations'' of the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accords. The Soviet <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, <PERSON> Vadim </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Perfilyev </PERSON>, told a government news briefing Thursday the <ORGANIZATION> Kremlin </ORGANIZATION> may reconsider its obligations under the agreements if the violations by <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> continue. However, he shied away from mentioning any potential Soviet reaction. The commander of Soviet forces in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> Gromov </PERSON>, said in a newspaper interview published Sunday that the violations could force his country to reconsider the withdrawal timetable. The Kremlin sent tanks and troops into <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in December 1979 to preside over the replacement of one Marxist leader by another. The Soviets stayed on to fight the guerrillas in a brutal war in which more than 13,000 <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> soldiers lost their lives.
