hat he wanted, which was solely to have taxes raised. ... That was not an antidote to get us out of recession'' in 1982. Some of the first term's major events were shown, including the assassination attempt, the October 1983 bombing of a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> barracks in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> that killed 243 military personnel and the invasion of <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION> two days later. Recalling the assassination attempt, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said: `` I heard what I thought was firecrackers. ... I did n't feel a bullet hit me.'' When asked what was his greatest achievement, he said: `` Sometimes I think,'' then laughed and continued, `` just staying alive.'' Even <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s critics praised his ability to control the media. `` These people have understood that they have a powerful instrument of news management in their hand,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Neustadt </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> professor and author of `` Presidential Power,'' who described <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s mastery of the photo opportunity and disdain of formal news conferences.
