<HEAD>Court Rules In Favor Of City In Convention Marches Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The city of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> won a ruling from the 11th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> on Friday in its dispute with demonstrators who sought to march on a street adjacent to the Democratic National Convention site. The appeals court noted that the city had given permission for demonstrators to march within one block of the buildings housing convention activities. `` The visibility of the parade from the actual convention site is not significantly diminished'' by holding it a block away, the court said. Alternative'88, a coalition of protest groups planning to demonstrate during next week's convention, had filed suit after the city refused to allow parades on a section of <LOCATION> Marietta </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION> next to the Omni Hotel and the <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> World Congress Center. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Orinda </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> ruled last week that the city has a `` significant'' government interest in guaranteeing delegates' access to the convention and therefore was justified in barring parades on the street from Monday through Thursday. The appeals court upheld the lower court ruling.
