<SECOND>AM-Chile-Letelier,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Rules Out Probe Into Slaying Of Allende Aide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rejected a request to reopen an investigation of the 1976 assassination in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> of a Chilean dissident. The request was filed by lawyers for the family of the dissident, <PERSON> Orlando </PERSON> <PERSON> Letelier </PERSON>, and was based on new testimony in a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> court by a former Chilean army major who acknowledged a role in the killing. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s unanimous ruling was made Thursday night and was published Friday by <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> newspapers. <PERSON> Letelier </PERSON> family lawyers argued that the new investigation was necessary following testimony before a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> court by <PERSON> Armando </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> <PERSON> Larios </PERSON>, the army major who surrendered to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> authorities in January 1987 and admitted to being an accomplice in the killing. Letelier and an American aide, <PERSON> Ronni </PERSON> <PERSON> Moffitt </PERSON>, were killed when a remote-control bomb blew up his car on Sept. 21, 1976, as it rounded <ORGANIZATION> Sheridan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circle </ORGANIZATION> on <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s Embassy Row. <PERSON> Letelier </PERSON>, a Socialist and former ambassador and <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> minister under Marxist President <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Allende </PERSON>, was a prominent and influential critic of the right-wing military government of President <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> took power in the 1973 coup that toppled <PERSON> Allende </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> said in its ruling that <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> <PERSON> Larios </PERSON>' <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> testimony `` can not be considered as better information.'' It also noted the testimony was made after a plea-bargain agreement. Plea bargaining is barred by Chilean law. In 1978, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> court indicted <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> <PERSON> Larios </PERSON> and two other Chilean army officers, all secret police agents, in connection with the Letelier killing. The Chilean <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rejected a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> request for the extradition of the three officers, but last year <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> <PERSON> Larios </PERSON> slipped out of the country and surrendered to <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> authorities in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. In 1987, the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration again called on <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> to hand over the other two officers, Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Contreras </PERSON>, a former secret police chief, and a top aide, Col. <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> Espoinoza </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> refused.
