<FIRST>r a AM-Lovers'Lawsuit     07-15 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lovers' Lawsuit,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Husband Can't Sue Wife's Lover over Children</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A husband ca n't sue his wife's lover for the emotional distress he suffered when he learned the lover had fathered her children, a state appeals court ruled. Courts should stay out of such affairs, it said Thursday. `` The innocent children here may suffer significant harm from having their family involved in litigation such as this,'' the 1st <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeal </ORGANIZATION> said in ordering the suit dismissed on `` public policy'' grounds. The court said, however, that a husband in such a situation might be able to sue for reimbursement of money he spent to support the children after being falsely told he was the father. The <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mateo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> case involved a divorced couple, identified by the court as <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> and <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON>, and her lover, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> During </PERSON> the affair, the court said, <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> gave birth to a daughter in 1983 and to a son in 1984. She sued for separation from <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> in 1985, saying at the time that the children were his. But in a settlement of the divorce case in January 1987, all parties agreed that <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> was the father. <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> sued <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> the next month, claiming fraud and intentional infliction of emotional distress, and sought $ 1.75 million in punitive damages. The suit said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> knew shortly after the births that he was the father of both children, but misled <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> into thinking he was the father, congratulating him and agreeing to be the daughter's godfather It was only after the children were one and two years old, and <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> and his parents had become emotionally attached to them, that he was told the truth, he said. Superior Court Judge <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> refused to dismiss the suit but was overruled by the appeals court on a 3-0 vote. While fraud and infliction of emotional distress normally are grounds for a damage suit, the subject of this suit `` is not one in which it is appropriate for the courts to intervene,'' said the opinion by Justice <PERSON> Jerome </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>. He distinguished the case from suits that have been allowed for deceit when a woman was infected with venereal disease that her lover had concealed, or when a woman suffered an abnormal pregnancy and needed a life-saving operation after her lover told her he was sterile. Both of those cases involved physical injuries and neither had a potential for harming innocent children, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. He also said allowing the suit would conflict with the public policy of encouraging natural fathers to acknowledge and support their children. `` Men in <PERSON> Richard </PERSON>'s situation, who are otherwise willing to voluntarily acknowledge and support their children, would have a strong disincentive to do so since revealing the truth would subject them to this type of tort action,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said.
