<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> ATLANTA </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- - <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON>, who lost the presidential race four years ago after a divided convention, said Friday Democrats must avoid allowing tensions between <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> from going so far they `` set poison down into the roots'' and spoil chances for the ticket in the fall. The former vice president, who is staying out of the spotlight while Democrats hold their convention in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> beginning Monday, said he hopes <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> will join in fully supporting the eventual Democratic ticket with <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> _ and believes he will despite tensions now. `` It is traditional, almost to be expected, that we'll have some struggles _ but it is how those struggles are conducted and whether they'll stay within the lines that allow the nominee to come out of the convention with a feeling in the public that he's ready to president,'' <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> said. `` I think Rev. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> knows that,'' he said. `` We always have rising tensions about this time; it's inherent. ... But I believe this is a year where Democrats understand these fights, if they're carried on too far, become too personalized, they set poison down into the roots that can be difficult to deal with.'' <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON>, in an interview with news agency reporters, also said he believes <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' failure to reach <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> by telephone to inform him of <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>'s selection as vice president was not an intentional slight. He said it should not be allowed to become the basis of crippling divisions. `` It was n't intentional,'' he said, noting that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> tried to call and was unsuccessful. `` I