<SECOND>AM-Beach Driving,0645</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Permits Four-Wheel Drive Vehicles On Cape Cod Seashore</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge has upheld <ORGANIZATION> Cape </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cod </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seashore </ORGANIZATION> guidelines allowing off-road vehicles on an eight-mile stretch of beach, defeating conservationists who claim the vehicles threaten the fragile ecosystem. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> ruled that off-road vehicle driving on <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cod </LOCATION>'s northern beaches `` is an appropriate public use ... and does not adversely affect the Seashore's natural, scenic and aesthetic values.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Audubon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Sierra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>, which sued over dune buggy use in 1981, appealed the decision to the 1st <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>. The conservationists contend that vehicles threaten shore bird nesting and the tender vegetation that stems erosion of the dunes. They also say vehicles destroy the natural beauty and interfere with other beach-goers. But <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> said in a ruling signed late last month that dune nesting and beach aesthetics are unaffected by the vehicles, and that conflicts between drivers and other beach users are minimal. Under amended rules issued in 1985, vehicles are limited to the eight-mile stretch from <LOCATION> Hatches </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> to High Head in <LOCATION> Truro </LOCATION>. Winter driving is prohibited and the beach is closed when tides, beach configurations or bird nesting make the route impassable. Just one of the Seashore's six public beaches, Race Point, is open to drivers, who must get a permit, have their vehicle inspected and watch a videotape on ecology. The Seashore issues about 2,000 permits a year, <ORGANIZATION> Cape </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cod </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seashore </ORGANIZATION> chief ranger <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonanno </PERSON> said Friday. All dune areas are off limits except a few tracts with deeded access rights. The ruling `` reinforces the fact that we have taken the appropriate steps to meet the natural resource objectives and meet the public interest,'' <ORGANIZATION> Cape </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cod </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seashore </ORGANIZATION> chief ranger <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonanno </PERSON> said Friday. The Cape Cod National Seashore, created by the 1961 federal Seashore Act, enacted a resource management plan in August 1981 to control increasing numbers of beach-goers and wheeled vehicles. The three conservation groups sued the day the plan took effect. The original plan allowed vehicles on 12 miles of beach from April to November, and on a 25-mile stretch in <LOCATION> Eastham </LOCATION> in winter. After an order from <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, the plan was amended in 1985. `` The court is basically saying, yes, the'85 plan is a resonable plan, it addresses adequately the balance of different uses, accommodates all visitors to the Seashore and protects its resources,'' <PERSON> Bonanno </PERSON> said. Conservationists say off-road vehicle use is prohibited under the Seashore Act, which bans action that `` would be incompatible with the preservation of the unique flora and fauna or the physiographic conditions now prevailing.'' But the act permits recreational development _ for activities such as fishing, camping and sailing _ that is environmentally `` compatible'' and `` appropriate'' to the beach. The government can ban off-road vehicle use if found to have adverse effects on soil, vegetation or wildlife habitats. The law foundation said policing drivers is difficult, that even small incursions on tender dune grass are harmful and that the Seashore has handed over one-fifth of the beach to drivers, who comprise just 3 percent of its 6 million annual users. `` The law did not envision the rampant off-road vehicle use that has gone on since the Seashore was created,'' foundation staff scientist <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Hauge </PERSON> said Friday. <PERSON> Bonanno </PERSON> said rangers last year filed 236 reports of dune buggy violations, issuing about 100 fines of $ 50 and 100 warnings. Seashore officials said most beach drivers are fishermen needing access to the tip of Race Point. A <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> survey found that only a small percentage of Seashore visitors opposed vehicle use or said they were displaced by it.
