<HEAD>Conference Cites Long Anti-Jewish Tradition In Christianity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A conference on the Holocaust on Friday accused <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> churches of centuries of anti-Jewish teaching, and one <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> expert said the tradition helps explain why <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> genocide went unchecked in <LOCATION> Christian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. `` The failure of European civilization to stem the tide of evil during the Holocaust makes it critically important to counteract historical and traditional Christian anti-Jewish teaching,'' said a statement issued by the international conference. The statement concluded a weeklong gathering of 500 academics, concentration camp survivors, theologians and teachers. The conference met in the university town of <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION> before moving to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> on Friday. Christian churchmen, including <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cardinal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Basil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hume </ORGANIZATION>, joined in prayers for the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION>' 6 million Jewish victims, and conference organizers read out messages from leaders of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>. West German Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> received a standing ovation for a message in which he acknowledged German responsibility for the Holocaust and said: `` We Germans are prepared to live with this terrible truth.'' President <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said, `` The words ` never again' must ever be the pledge of all who pause in remembrance of those who have perished.'' A major theme of the conference was how Christians allowed the World War II slaughter of Jews to happen. Delegates focused on longtime Christian church teachings that the Jews were responsible for the murder of <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Christ </PERSON> and were condemned to wander without a homeland. Most churches have since stopped espousing this belief, including the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in 1965. The Rev. <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> Littel </PERSON>, an American Methodist minister and a leading academic expert on the Holocaust, said that despite `` an acute rise in sensitivity -LRB- by Christian churches toward Jews -RRB- in the past 25 years ... the problem remains.'' `` Why do you suppose the liberal <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> churches find it so hard to come to terms with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>?'' asked <PERSON> Littel </PERSON>, a former professor of religion at <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> and at the <ORGANIZATION> Hebrew </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>. `` It is because they are used to teaching that the Jew is a loser,'' <PERSON> Littel </PERSON> said in an interview. `` They've been teaching for centuries that he is supposed to wander, supposed to be miserable.'' <PERSON> Littel </PERSON> said that in 1936, <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> bishops courageously protested the persecution of Jews. But he said the <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> response was `` what are you complaining about _ we're just doing what your churches have been teaching about all along.'' The Anglican bishop of <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION>, the Rt. Rev. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Christians </PERSON> had to examine `` how it is that at the heart of a so-called Christian civilization, such unspeakable atrocities could be perpetrated.'' <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> heads an Anglican committee which will submit a new policy document on the church's relations with Jews to the Lambeth Conference, an international gathering of Anglican bishops opening Monday. Several participants at the conference paid tribute to Christians who helped Jews during the Holocaust. Historian <PERSON> Yehuda </PERSON> <PERSON> Bauer </PERSON> noted that 24 British doctors, only one of whom was a Jew, went to treat those being liberated from <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION> concentration camp. Many of the prisoners were known to have typhoid and none of the doctors who volunteered had received immunizations. As a result, many of them died. The conference was sponsored by publisher <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON>, 65, a Czechoslovak-born Jew who fled to <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> as a teen-ager, and his French Protestant wife, <PERSON> Elisabeth </PERSON>. <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON> asked delegates to stand and applaud after reading out <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>'s message. `` Germans became guilty of that crime -LRB- the Holocaust -RRB- as individuals, but they are collectively liable for the injustice committed in their name,'' <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION>, said in his message. `` No one can rule out the possiblity of comparable atrodcities happening again,'' <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>'s message added. `` It must not be forgotten.''
