<HEAD>State Department Pressed To Lift Suspension of Soviet Refugees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Twenty-three senators and nine <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members on Friday called for an immediate end to the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s suspension of refugee processing, which has left thousands of prospective immigrants to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> temporarily stranded in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> The senators told President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in a letter: `` This decision sends a terrible signal to those seeking freedom all over the world, and could give the Soviets the opportunity to claim that it is <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and not the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> which is impeding emigration.'' The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members, all members of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on refugees, asked Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> either to find the estimated $ 10 million required to resume refugee processing at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> or to ask <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for additional funds. The suspension went into effect on July 4 and is scheduled to last until Oct. 1 It came after a sudden surge in the number of visa applications by Soviet citizens, mostly Armenians and Jews, and after the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration had increased the annual number of refugees the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would accomodate. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> relaxed emigration policies recently and in June the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> embassy issued some 2,000 refugee visas, more than the total approved for all of the 1987 fiscal year which began Oct. 1, 1986. `` In light of the promises this country has made to welcome and resettle thousands of emigres from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, the suspension should be lifted immediately,'' the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members told <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> in a letter. They said the suspension will result in the `` forced displacement of many families who have already lost their homes and their jobs, and who, in many cases, have made long journeys to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to begin refugee processing.'' `` After urging the Soviets to open the gate of emigration, it is important that we find this funding for refugee assistance, the letter said. `` To do otherwise could leave thousands of people in a state of uncertainty and desperation, and send a disturbing signal that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is unwilling to back up its commitment to accomodate those seeking refuge.'' Rep. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schumer </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, who initiated the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> letter, said his attention was drawn to the situation when a couple with four children he been attempting to help leave the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> were told the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> embassy could not process their applications for three months. <PERSON> Schumer </PERSON> said two members of the family of <PERSON> Zoltan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Pepa </PERSON> <PERSON> Forkosh </PERSON> are sick and two are infants. He said they had traveled to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> from the <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION>, have been compelled to move into an expensive apartment and are rapidly using up their funds. Other signers of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> letter were Reps. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON>, R-Ga.; <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON>, D-Conn.; <