<NOTE>For release at 6 p .m. EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>Baltimore Scientists Find Key Protein In Detecting Aromas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A complex protein produced in a nasal gland has been identified by researchers as the chemical messenger that carries aromas to the odor-sensing nerves of the nose. Dr. <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON> <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> said Friday he and three other researchers have cloned the gene that gives instructions for the creation of the protein and may one day be able to use the protein to sharpen the sense of smell. The protein, called the odorant binding protein or OBP, is secreted by the lateral nasal gland and then carried by a duct to the tip of the nose, <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON> said. When air is inhaled, the OBP is sprayed as fine mist into the air that flows into the nose, he said. <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON> said the protein binds with airborne molecules as they are inhaled and is then carried past a nerve bundle that picks up the chemical message of the odor. `` The nerve endings are way back, high in the nose,'' <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. `` Only a small portion of the nose has these receptors.'' When the OBP comes in contact with the receptors, the nerves interpret the chemistry of the OBP as a particular smell. <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON> said the precise mechanism of how the nerves can distinguish between different smells, such as sweet and sour, is not yet understood. He said what is detected as a fragrance may actually be caused by the chemical reaction of the OBP mixed with the fragrance molecule. By cloning the gene that produces the <ORGANIZATION> OBP </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON> said his team should be able to produce large quantities of the protein and conduct further studies into the sense of smell, one of the least understood of the senses. Use of OBP may be of medical significance in restoring lost appetite or helping patients who have totally lost the sense of smell. `` This could help the elderly regain their appetite,'' said <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON>. `` As people age, they lose their sense of smell'' and this often is the reason that older people stop eating as they should. By spraying OBP into the nose, he said, it may help restore some of the sense of smell. <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON> said much more research must be conducted before specific, clinical uses for the OBP are found. A report on the study was published Friday in Science, the journal of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> for the Advancement of Science. Others on the OBP research team are <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Pevsner </PERSON>, also of <PERSON> Johns </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> and <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Feinstein </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Howard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hughes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
