<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sixteen years after he was expelled from the Soviet Writers Union for allegedly urging Jews to emigrate, <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> songwriter <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Galich </PERSON> has been posthumously reinstated, it was reported Friday. The action by the writers union amounts to a rehabilitation of the popular Jewish bard once condemned by the official press as a `` traitor'' and a drunkard with a `` pathological lust for money.'' The announcement by the official <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency called <PERSON> Galich </PERSON> `` a talented poet, songster and playwright'' who was unjustly vilified. `` Bureaucrats responsible for culture in the 1970s closed the doors to the press and the motion pictures industry before him and then hounded him out of the country for what they considered ` seditious' writings,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Galich </PERSON>'s satire about official hypocrisy, the apathy of the Soviet masses and the labor camps that dot the nation made him unpopular with authorities. But he was a hit among the people, who listened to his songs on tapes circulated underground and read them in books published abroad. The writers union, accusing <PERSON> Galich </PERSON> of `` agitation for the emigration of Soviet Jews to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>,'' expelled him from its ranks in January 1972. <PERSON> Galich </PERSON>, who wrote screenplays in addition to songs, was also expelled from the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cinema </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>. He left the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in 1974 and died in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> three years later. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> did not say when the writers union readmitted <PERSON> Galich </PERSON>. It also did not say whether he was readmitted to the film workers union. Since coming to power in March 1985, Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has encouraged the rehabilitation of cultural figures once disgraced in official eyes. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> noted that in recent months, several literary journals have published poems by <PERSON> Galich </PERSON> and a play he wrote 30 years ago, subsequently banned, has just premiered in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>.
