<HEAD>Carter Says Communication Key for Dukakis, Jackson</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Wrtier</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, declaring his services as a mediator unneeded, said Friday that the relatively minor differences between <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> could vanish `` if the two men understood each other a little bit better.'' `` The compatability between <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and their followers are so overwhelming that the differences are relatively insignicant,'' <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said in an interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> at the Carter Presidential Center. `` I do n't think they need any mediation,'' he said. `` I think what is needed is to just have a better means of communication directly with one another and to get any misunderstandings resolved as early as possible in the convention.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, who sought to be named <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' vice presidential candidate, seemed miffed when the pick went to Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and word got out before <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> personally relayed the decison to <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. He said Thursday that he had asked <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> to act as mediator between his and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' camps. However, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> rejected that idea Friday, and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> aides also expressed doubts about it. <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said if any mediation is needed the role should go to <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> but that he might get involved if <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> asked him to. However, <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> also said he saw no role for a mediator. The former president said he did not see ill will over the vice