<HEAD>Wholesale Prices Up
^With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here, at a glance, are developments in the economic picture Friday:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>TRADE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit rose in May to $ 10.9 billion, but the imbalance was the second smallest in almost three years, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported. The gap between imports and exports widened by $ 627 million from a revised April imbalance of $ 10.3 billion. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports climbed 2.3 percent in May to $ 26.6 billion, while imports rose 3.4 percent to $ 37.6 billion.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WHOLESALE PRICES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Wholesale prices edged up a moderate 0.4 percent in June, but drought sent prices for raw food soaring at their steepest pace in more than 2 -LCB- years. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said raw costs jumped 4.2 percent last month, a rate not seen since the 5.1 percent climb of October 1985. Prices for foods ready to be retailed rose 1.1 percent, reflecting earlier, though less severe, increases in raw food costs.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BUSINESS INVENTORIES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Business inventories in May rose a moderate 0.6 percent, held in check by a 0.9 percent jump in sales, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said. Inventories rose $ 4.4 billion to a seasonally adjusted $ 728.4 billion while sales rose $ 4.2 billion to $ 483.7 billion. The May gain followed a 0.5 percent climb in April and a 0.4 percent increase in March. The jump in business sales came after a month of no change in April and a steep increase of 1.9 percent in March.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>INDUSTRIAL PRODUCTION</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industrial production, boosted by heavy demand for electricity during the summer heat wave, climbed 0.4 percent in June, the ninth consecutive month without a decline. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> said the June advance followed identical gains of 0.5 percent in both April and May and left output 5.8 percent higher than it was a year ago.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>U.S. STOCK MARKET</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Stock prices posted a moderate gain in an erratic session. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 15.83 to 2,129.45, finishing the week with a net gain of 23.30.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DOLLAR</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The dollar zoomed to recent highs against several major currencies. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, the dollar finished at 133.40 yen, up 0.45 yen from Thursday's close. Later in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 135.35 yen. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> the dollar closed at 135.45 yen, up from 133.18 yen on Thursday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar gained more than 2.5 cents against the British pound to reach its highest level since October. It cost $ 1.6635 to buy one pound, cheaper than $ 1.6890 late Thursday. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the pound cost $ 1.6605, far cheaper than Thursday's $ 1.6875
</TEXT>
<HEAD>RETAIL SALES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Retail sales rose 0.5 percent to a seasonally adjusted $ 132.8 billion last month, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported Thursday. It said sales rose 0.3 in May, an upward revision from the previous estimate of 0.1 percent. The strength in June came at department stores and other general merchandise outlets, where sales jumped 1.87 percent to $ 15.2 billion.
