<HEAD>Food Shortages, Illnesses Rampant in Disputed Region</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 18th pvs, Asked what ... UPDATING with
other strike effects. PICKS up 19th graf pvs, Armenian activists .
..</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Food shortages and illnesses caused by stress are plaguing Armenians living in a disputed region trying to break away from <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>, a resident and the state-run media reported Friday. One resident, a journalist with the state broadcasting authority, claimed <LOCATION> Azerbaijani </LOCATION> authorities were preventing food from getting to the region, <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>. `` We are under a virtual economic blockade,'' said the journalist. `` The Azerbaijanis are trying to morally kill our movement, to strike down our just demands.'' The official news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>, however, blamed the supply problems in <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> on a nearly 2-month-old strike. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said more than 130 freight cars and more than 300 containers of food have backed up at the railway station in <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>'s main city. `` There are no more fruits or vegetables in our shops,'' said the reporter, who spoke on condition he not be identified by name. `` We have almost no economic ties now with <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>.'' Ethnic Armenians make up more than three-quarters of <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>'s 160,000 people and most are <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION>. They have complained for months of economic, cultural and religious discrimination by the <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> government. Early this year, they began protesting and demanded that control of the region, given to predominantly Moslem <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> in 1923, be transferred to the neighboring republic of <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. In February, 32 people were killed in ethnic riots in <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>, 26 of them Armenians. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said residents were suffering because of the tensions in the region. `` The population of <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION> is exhausted by the situation that has arisen. People have forgotten about weddings and family holidays. The incidence of illnesses caused by excessive stress has grown,'' the news agency reported. It said an Armenian resident was being sought after murdering his wife and two relatives, seriously wounding a 2-year-old child of his sister-in-law and trying to kill his son. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said the suspect, G.S. <PERSON> Adamyan </PERSON>, has a criminal record but that the motive for the attack was not known. The journalist said <PERSON> Azerbaijaini </PERSON> authorities refused Thursday to allow a plane of the state-run airlines <ORGANIZATION> Aeroflot </ORGANIZATION> from the Armenian capital of <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> to land in <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION>. Instead, the airliner touched down in the Armenian city of <LOCATION> Goris </LOCATION>, he said. The Azerbaijanis, the journalist added, have suspended bus service between <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION> and the Armenian cities of <LOCATION> Kirovakan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kafan </LOCATION>, but buses have been leaving <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION> for <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> with a police escort. The legislature of the Delaware-size region voted Tuesday to secede and join <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. But the Azerbaijani government voided the decision within hours. A general strike in solidarity with <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> residents, begun July 4, was continuing in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, sources said. <PERSON> Khovik </PERSON> <PERSON> Vasilyan </PERSON>, an Armenian activist, said by telephone from <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> that most of the factories in the city of 1.1 million people were still on strike but that transportation was functioning normally. Asked what the prospects were for resolving the 5-month-old dispute, a woman reached by phone in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> sighed and said: `` I do n't know what will happen. We are in a difficult situation.'' Soviet television reported Friday that many workers at a <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> alarm clock factory were idle and not receiving pay because an Armenian factory that makes electronic parts was on strike. The newscast portrayed life as normal in <LOCATION> Susha </LOCATION>, the second biggest city in <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>, despite what it said were rumors in <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION> that <LOCATION> Azerbaijani </LOCATION> residents had attacked Armenians there. Armenian activists have scheduled a rally outside <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>'s repository of ancient Armenian manuscripts for Saturday night They believe the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, the highest legislative body in the Soviet government, will meet Monday and they hope it will consider the <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> question. Soviet officials have said such a meeting is likely but have not given a date. Pravda, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> daily, said Thursday the work stoppage in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> had cost $ 65 million in lost production and that $ 29 million worth of construction had not been completed. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said that about 20,000 Azerbaijanis living in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> had fled to <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> and that as of Wednesday, 7,265 Armenians who once lived in <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION> and other <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> cities had returned to <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>.
