<HEAD>Dukakis Defends Use of Taxes and Borrowing to Close State Deficit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> defended his use of taxes and borrowing to cover a state budget shortfall as he awaited final legislative action on the plan before heading to the Democratic convention. In an interview Friday with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in his Statehouse office, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> rejected any comparisons between his borrowing and the federal deficit spending of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. `` Obviously, we're not going to do anything around here that jeopardizes our credit rating. If all goes well, we'll come out of this with some end-of-year surplus,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> predicted. He also defended his recent signing of a $ 24 million sales tax on cigarettes on the grounds that it would pay for the first year phase-in of his universal health care plan. `` If we did n't have the health care bill, we would n't have needed that. Frankly, I think that's a modest price to pay for the first universal health care bill in the history of this country,'' the governor said. He acknowledged, however, that the cigarette tax would not pay for universal health insurance in later years when the program becomes more expensive. He did not address himself to the other revenue measures proposed to shore up next year's state budget. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> did show a willingness to tangle with <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> if the expected Republican presidential nominee accuses him of being a tax-raiser. `` Let'em do it,'' said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, who recently accused <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> of violating a no-new-taxes pledge by supporting a federal catastrophic illness health care bill that calls for $ 6 billion in new revenues. `` I have n't heard much the last week or two from the vice president on the subject, since his no-tax pledge has disappeared. And I do n't think you're going to hear much,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. As he spoke Friday afternoon, an $ 11.75 billion budget for the current fiscal year was awaiting his signature. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said he would use his line-item veto to reduce the total, but he would not say how. At the same time, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is awaiting a package of bills designed to close a deficit in last year's budget that ranges from the administration's estimate of $ 370 million to as much as $ 470 million projected by some legislators. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has proposed closing the budget gap through converting some $ 200 million in operating expenses into long-term bonds, tapping a $ 27 million pension system surplus and diverting $ 50 million in surplus lottery proceeds from local government. In addition, to shore up next year's budget, the governor is seeking to raise more than $ 200 million by closing corporate tax `` loopholes,'' re-coupling the state income tax with federal law and collecting unclaimed bottle deposits. The governor traced his budget problems to an unanticipated _ and, he says, unforeseeble _ downturn in state tax collections this spring. `` Remember this,'' he said, `` The <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, as recently as three months ago, gave us a revised report, which forecast a $ 70 million shortfall for FY88 and a $ 40 million shortfall for FY89. `` Now, if that revised forecast had been accurate, it would have been like a day at the beach,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. According to the governor, he and legislative leaders made a decision last year to take advantage of the now-evaporated state budget surplus by paying cash for some highway and building repair projects that normally would have been funded through bonds. Now, faced with a shortfall, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said he is simply shifting the funds back into a category where they belonged all along.
