ing of future contracts.'' The list includes some of the nation's largest defense contractors, including <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION>. Two weeks ago, <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> announced he was suspending contracts in nine military programs worth $ 1 billion because of the possibility they may have been tainted. He said he was acting on the basis of information contained in an affidavit unsealed by a federal court in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> rescinded that action Monday and told <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> a review of the contracts had found no problems with the pacts. But he also said action should be taken as a warning to contractors that the Pentagon would act if questions were raised about future contracts. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> and other <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials have said the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> has the legal authority to recoup profits if the money turns out to have been earned through some illegality. But members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> have been pushing for inclusion of a separate clause in future contracts to spell out that right more clearly. The firms affected by Friday's announcement include <ORGANIZATION> Armtec </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Palatka </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Cubic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Emhart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGA