<HEAD>Get Rid of Cash-Based Accounting in U.S. Government, GAO Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The federal government should adopt uniform accounting principles to replace some 200 separate, antiquated systems it now uses, and create a chief financial officer to oversee the entire financial picture, according to a report released Thursday. `` There is a recognition today that most of the government's accounting systems are outdated, inefficient and ineffective, and that improvements in financial management are urgently needed,'' said the report by the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' investigative `` Getting this <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report is really important because it confirms our worst fears,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> DioGuardi </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, who says he is the only practicing certified public accountant in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. `` There are so many aspects to what is structurally and systemically wrong.'' <PERSON> DioGuardi </PERSON> and Rep. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Craig </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Idaho </LOCATION>, released the report at a news conference. The report had been requested by <PERSON> Craig </PERSON>, the ranking Republican on the Government Operations subcommittee on commerce, consumer and monetary affairs. Among the report's recommendations: _ Create a federal chief financial officer within the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> who would have the power to oversee and direct the financial management, accounting and budget systems of the federal government; _ Prepare audited financial statements every year in every major department and agency; _ Change from the current cash-basis -LRB- one-year -RRB- accounting system to a long and short term, or accrual, system; _ Adopt uniform accounting systems in every department and major agency, replacing the more than 200 systems `` We've got to get some better accountability, some better controls and some better information,'' said <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON>, director of <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>'s accounting and financial management division, who attended the news conference.
