<HEAD>Gorbachev Meets Leaders, Raisa Visits Auschwitz</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs with dinner toasts. PICKS up 4th pvs `Mrs.
Gorbachev'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> spent Friday in closed meetings with other <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact leaders, and his wife <PERSON> Raisa </PERSON> visited <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION>, where 4 million people were killed in Nazi death camps. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s proposals for new efforts to break a deadlock with <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> over reducing conventional forces in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, already rejected by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, were among the topics for discussion in the first of two days of private talks. A brief official report of the proceedings said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and the other leaders addressed the opening-day session, but gave no details. They met in the Council of Ministers Palace, where the Treaty of <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> was signed in 1955 to formalize the political and military alliance. The official news agency <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> later reported dinner toasts by <PERSON> Nicolae </PERSON> <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> and Polish leader <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>. <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> called for talks aimed at eliminating short-range nuclear missiles in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> _ those with ranges up to 300 miles, which are not included in the U.S.-Soviet treaty to scrap medium-range weapons, the agency said. <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s proposals for talks on reducing conventional forces were `` valuable, original initiatives'' and were discussed in the first day's session. Mrs. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> returned to southern <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, which the <PERSON> Gorbachevs </PERSON> visited earlier in the week, to memorialize those who died during World War II in the <LOCATION> Auschwitz-Birkenau </LOCATION> extermination camp. She laid bouquets of red carnations at Execution Wall and at the Russian-language tablet that is part of an international monument to the dead. Wiping a tear from her cheek, Mrs. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said after touring the camp that almost 50 years since the beginning of World War II the camp still reminds the living of `` the hope, human fear and bravery'' of its inmates. `` It should remind us all that what is most precious in this world is the right to live and be free,'' she said in brief remarks broadcast by state television. Soviet forces liberated <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION>, built by the Germans after they occupied <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> at the beginning of the war, in January 1945 and it has been preserved as a museum. The gas chambers and crematoria of <LOCATION> Birkenau </LOCATION> were largely destroyed by retreating German forces, and the site is marked by a stone monument and tablets in many languages. The combined camp was the center of <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s effort to wipe out European Jews, millions of whom lived in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and Nazi-occupied regions of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Next to Poles, both Jew and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION>, more than 1 million Soviet citizens made up the largest single nationality among the victims. Soviet prisoners of war received particularly harsh treatment in the slave-labor sections of the complex. News coverage of Mrs. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s visit, the first event of the six-day visit to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> when she did not accompany her husband, was restricted to Soviet and Polish media. The meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION>'s political-consultative council is the first since the fourth Gorbachev-Reagan summit six weeks ago in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. It also was the Soviet leader's first opportunity to brief his allies on the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s national <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> conference at the end of June, which reiterated his policy of encouraging economic and social reform. When he arrived Monday, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> proposed that negotiators from East and West meet informally to seek ways of breaking the impasse that for years has blocked mutual reductions of conventional forces in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> issued a statement saying appropriate forums already exist in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> and elsewhere for discussing arms reduction and that any such talks should include representatives of all <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> countries. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> response was equally cool to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s suggestion that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> would withdraw an unspecified number of its military aircraft from <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> if <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> drops a plan to redeploy 72 American F-16s from <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>.
