<HEAD>PRECEDE BONN, West Germany</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Natalya </PERSON> <PERSON> Solzhenitsyn </PERSON>, the wife of Soviet emigre writer <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Solzhenitsyn </PERSON>, on Friday denied a German radio report that she and her husband would return to their homeland for a visit and that his works would be published there. `` Everything is -LRB- a -RRB- lie. Everything is false,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Solzhenitsyn </PERSON> said in a telephone interview with The Associated Press from her home in <LOCATION> Cavendish </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vt </LOCATION>. The Munich-based <ORGANIZATION> Bayerischer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rundfunk </ORGANIZATION> radio station said <PERSON> Solzhenitsyn </PERSON> and his wife planned to visit the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in November or December and that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> wanted to publish all his works, including the novella `` Cancer Ward'' and `` The Gulag Archipelago.'' It said the information came from its correspondent in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. In an interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, the New York-based correspondent said <PERSON> Solzhenitsyn </PERSON>'s wife told him by telephone Wednesday that Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> had written two letters to her husband with offers to return and to have <PERSON> Solzhenitsyn </PERSON>'s works published in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The correspondent asked that his name not be used. Mrs. <PERSON> Solzhenitsyn </PERSON> said, `` I never talked to -LRB- an -RRB- unnamed reporter from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>.'' `` I can not confirm -LRB- the report -RRB-,'' she said. She also said she could not speculate on the report's origin or motive. `` I have no idea. I have no comment at all.'' Earlier, Mrs. <PERSON> Solzhenitsyn </PERSON>, who rarely speaks to reporters, spoke to an aide to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Jeffords </PERSON>, R-Vt., and denied that her husband had received letters from <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> The aide, <PERSON> Bernice </PERSON> <PERSON> Murray </PERSON>, quoted her as saying, `` It's a lie. The interviews never took place ... It's absurd.'' <PERSON> Solzhenitsyn </PERSON> incurred the wrath of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s Communist leadership with novels such as `` One Day in the Life of <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Denisovich </PERSON>,'' `` Cancer Ward'' and `` The First Circle,'' as well as the non-fiction work `` The Gulag Archipelago,'' an expose of terror and hopelessness in Soviet labor camps. He won the Nobel Prize for Literature in 1970. In February 1974, <PERSON> Solzhenitsyn </PERSON> was arrested, formally accused of treason, stripped of his citizenship and deported to the West. In June, <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zalygin </PERSON>, editor of the Soviet monthly Novy Mir, said negotiations for publishing `` Cancer Ward'' in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> were under way. However, Mrs. <PERSON> Solzhenitsyn </PERSON> was quoted by <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> as saying at the time that Soviet officials had not approached <PERSON> Solzhenitsyn </PERSON> about publishing any of his works in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.
