<HEAD>More Record-Breaking Heat in Midwest; Storms Around Omaha</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Temperature records continue to fall Friday in parts of the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, and severe storms injured several people, damaged buildings and knocked out power in the <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neb. </LOCATION>, area and parts of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>. By early aftenoon, readings passing the century mark were common across the <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> deserts, as well as portions of <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. The temperature reached 102 in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> on Friday, beating an 11-year-old record by 3 degrees. Another record fell there, too: It was the fifth time this year that temperatures had reached triple digits in the Windy City, more than any other year on record. In <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>, the thermometer reached 91 degrees by early afternoon to make the 12th consecutive day of 90 degree or greater temperatures. This equals the record string of 90-degree days set in July 1881. Other temperature records were set in <LOCATION> Eau </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Claire </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, 101, besting the 1936 record by 1 degree; <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Crosse </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, 102, beating the 1931 record by 3 degrees; <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, 98, beating the 1901 record by 2 degrees; and <LOCATION> Rockford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, 101, beating the 1932 record by 1 degree. Records were tied in Minneapolis-St. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>, 101; and in <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hatteras </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, 90 In Council Bluffs, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, thunderstorms packing tornadoes caused extensive damage in a residential area. At least eight people were reported being treated at hospitals at Council Bluffs, officials said. Most of the injuries were described as minor. Strong winds associated with the storms downed trees and broke windows and wind and lightning caused scattered power outages throughout the <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION> metropolitan area, of which <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bluffs </ORGANIZATION> is a part. A wind gust of 92 mph was reported at <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Eppley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airfield </ORGANIZATION>, the weather service reported. A severe thunderstorm watch continued in effect for parts of <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>. Elsewhere, heavy rain caused street flooding in parts of the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> panhandle early in the afternoon, and small trees, limbs and signs were reported blown down. At least two persons were hit by lightning. Earlier Friday, strong thunderstorms, sometimes accompanied by hail, moved through northern <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> and the northern half of <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>. One person suffered a broken leg when thunderstorm winds downed a tree in <LOCATION> Vilas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said. A waterspout moved onshore at <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Petersburg </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, causing minor roof damage to one house. Heavier rainfall for the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT included 0.83 inch at <LOCATION> Grand </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neb </LOCATION>.; 0.74 inch at <LOCATION> Green </LOCATION> <L