<HEAD>Thailand to Move Cambodian Refugees Closer to Border</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Authorities will begin moving about 17,000 Cambodian refugees from the Khao-I-Dang camp to a location closer to the Thai-Cambodian border, a military commander said Friday. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other countries have expressed concern about the refugees' safety if they are moved from <LOCATION> Khao-I-Dang </LOCATION>, whic is eight miles from the frontier. Thousands of Cambodians have entered <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> to escape the war in their country between guerrilla forces and Vietnamese and government troops. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> sent troops into <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> in December 1978, ousted the radical <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> regime and installed another communist government. Most of the Cambodians settled in camps along the border, and <PERSON> Khao-I-Dang </PERSON> is considered the only refugee camp not controlled by the differerent guerrilla groups. It also is the only camp where there is an official program to resettle the refugees in other countries. <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> had declared on Dec. 31, 1986, that it would close Khao-I-Dang, but only a small number of refugees were forced to leave. Col. <PERSON> Sanan </PERSON> <PERSON> Kajornklam </PERSON>, of the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION>'s Joint Operations Center, spoke of moving the refugees at a meeting Friday. Later, in an interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Sanan </PERSON> said that within three months authorities will start moving the <LOCATION> Khao-I-Dang </LOCATION> refugees to the area of Site 2 close to the border. Site 2 adjoins the Ban Thad camp where the government, trying to discourage more Indochinese from entering <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, has placed about 3,000 Vietnamese refugees. <PERSON> Sanan </PERSON> said the Khao-I-Dang refugees would be resettled because they have not been accepted by other countries and they must prepare to return to <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. `` If we close Khao-I-Dang, the Cambodians will know that they must go home,'' <PERSON> Sanan </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Kobsak </PERSON> <PERSON> Chutikul </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>'s Social Afffairs Division, said that in its plans to move the <LOCATION> Khao-I-Dang </LOCATION> refugees the government will follow three objectives that <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> outlined in a letter to the government last year. He said those objectives are that the new site be safe, that it be neutral and that the refugees remain under the protection of the office of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> High Commissioner for Refugees.
