<HEAD>NJ Company Expands Insurance Plan But States Still Unsatisfied</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MELANIE MADER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A company accused of reneging on a drought insurance offer said Friday it would issue an additional $ 10 million in total coverage for farmers in 10 <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> states. But one insurance official said <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s plan was unacceptable. Federal, a subsidiary of Warren-based <ORGANIZATION> Chubb </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cos. </ORGANIZATION>, has been accused of backing off a promise to issue policies that pay off if rainfall falls below a certain level. <ORGANIZATION> Chubb </ORGANIZATION> says the flood of applications in the final days of the enrollment period, which lasted from May 1 to June 17, exceeded the amount of coverage it wanted to provide, and that it can not fill all the applications. The company initially planned to issue $ 30 million but increased the total coverage to $ 40 million, which will protect about 800 farmers. <ORGANIZATION> Chubb </ORGANIZATION> said Friday it made the decision after talking with insurance commissioners in the affected states. The 6,000 farmers who do not receive insurance will get twice the amount of their premium returned, said <ORGANIZATION> Chubb </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Lu </PERSON> <PERSON> Korkuch </PERSON>. Premiums already have been returned to insurance agents, she said. Another 1,000 farmers whose applications were received June 16 or later will get only their premium back, she said. `` -LRB- Farmers -RRB- are n't losing money,'' she said. `` They just might not get the insurance they want.'' Applications for about $ 350 million in total coverage are not being accepted because they exceed the $ 40 million limit, she said. <ORGANIZATION> Chubb </ORGANIZATION> said Friday any assertion that it was bound to accept all applications was `` without merit'' and would be subject to a `` very vigorous defense.'' The company said nearly all the applications clearly indicate that policies would be issued only after acceptance by the insurer. `` It's hogwash,'' <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> Commissioner <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Hager </PERSON> said of that contention. `` The application form we approved for use in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> specifically provides that once the premium is submitted, coverage is bound,'' <PERSON> Hager </PERSON> said. `` We simply are not going to tolerate, by analogy, a company that issues a policy, finds out that the building is burning and says, ` Whoops we really did n't mean we were going to cover the loss,''' the <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> commissioner said. <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> officials said their states are prepared to take legal action if necessary, while <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> will seek to revoke the company's state license to do business if it does not provide the coverage. An estimated 450 <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> farmers applied and sent in premiums for the insurance, said <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Rector </PERSON>, deputy director of the <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION>. About 10 percent of them would be covered under <ORGANIZATION> Chubb </ORGANIZATION>'s proposal, he said. <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> Commerce Commissioner <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> estimates 1,000 farmers from his state applied for a total of $ 40 million in coverage. Other states whose farmers sought the coverage are <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOC