<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rebels mounted three attacks in northern and central <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> in violation of a truce with the Sandinista government, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said Friday. Its report said three of the U.S.-supported rebels, known as Contras, and one civilian were killed in the fighting and the Contras kidnapped 20 people. The ministry statement said that in one of the attacks on Thursday, three Contras died in a shootout with an army patrol in northern <LOCATION> Matagalpa </LOCATION> province. It also said the Contras ambushed an army truck in northern <LOCATION> Jinotega </LOCATION> province, kidnapping 16 people on board, and that four other people were abducted by the rebels and a civilian was killed in central Chontales province. The statement gave no details of the fighting and said nothing of any government casualties. The Contras and the leftist Sandinista government have accused each other of truce violations on and off since the cease-fire began March 21. Representatives from both sides held meetings to try to reach a peace accord without success. The last round of talks in June ended in deadlock and no new meetings were scheduled. The Sandinistas celebrate nine years in power next Tuesday. The insurrection they led in July 1979 ended 42 years of rule by the rightist, pro-American Somoza dynasty. The army announced on Friday a series of military exercises to defend <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>, the capital, in case of attack. The <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> have long claimed the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> eventually plans to invade <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. On Monday, the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> expelled <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Melton </PERSON> and seven other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomats, accusing them of conspiring to undermine the government. The <ORGAN