<SECOND>AM-Star Wars-Laser,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teller Claimed X-Ray Laser Could Destroy All Land-Based Soviet
Missiles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hydrogen bomb developer <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Teller </PERSON> once told a top administration arms control adviser that a proposed `` Star Wars'' laser could `` potentially shoot down the entire Soviet land-based missile force,'' a congressional report says. That and some other details in the report back the charge by a disaffected former director of the X-ray laser research program that <PERSON> Teller </PERSON> made unsupportable claims about the potential of the proposed weapon, Rep. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said Friday. `` Let me plead guilty to the great crime of optimism,'' Teller countered Friday. <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Woodruff </PERSON> resigned in 1985 as director of the <ORGANIZATION> Lawrence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Livermore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION>'s research program into the X-ray laser because of the dispute, and said he was demoted to an entry-level job. Last year, <PERSON> Woodruff </PERSON> filed grievances alleging that Teller and another scientist, <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> <PERSON> Wood </PERSON>, made `` overly optimistic, technically incorrect statements regarding this research to the nation's highest policy-makers.'' He also accused <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Batzel </PERSON>, then the lab's director, of blocking his efforts to correct those statements. An internal study eventually concluded that <PERSON> Woodruff </PERSON> was made into an `` unperson'' because of his dispute with <PERSON> Batzel </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> report, written at <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>'s request, cited some optimistic statements by Teller and <PERSON> Wood </PERSON> but also concluded that <PERSON> Woodruff </PERSON> and his colleagues at <LOCATION> Livermore </LOCATION> shared that optimism to some extent `` The report is trying to straddle the fence,'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said by phone from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` It says that <PERSON> Woodruff </PERSON> made similar -LRB- optimistic -RRB- statements, but that in a couple of instances _ the two <PERSON> Woodruff </PERSON> objected to most _ the statements -LRB- by Teller and Wood -RRB- were indeed overly optimistic and not factual.'' Teller, interviewed by telephone from <LOCATION> Livermore </LOCATION>, contended the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report backs his point of view. The report, he said, shows that <PERSON> Woodruff </PERSON>'s criticisms were over the way Teller worded his claims, but that <PERSON> Woodruff </PERSON> `` supported -LRB- them -RRB- in substance.'' The claim about the laser being able to shoot down all 10,000 Soviet land-based missiles sounds absurd because it was quoted out of context, the physicist said. `` I tried to illustrate the possibly great effects that the X-ray laser might produce,'' Teller said. `` If you read the letter, you will find qualifiers: ` eventually,' ` potentially' and ` perhaps.''' In a telephone interview, <PERSON> Woodruff </PERSON> also contended that the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report generally backs his point of view, but he had some criticism for it. The report, he said Friday, `` establishes everything I ever alleged, but I am very unhappy with the finding that suggests there was a great deal of similarity between Dr. <PERSON> Teller </PERSON> and myself.'' `` He was an enthusiast for the X-ray laser and I was an enthusiast. But the points we differed on were very important,'' <PERSON> Woodruff </PERSON> said, adding, `` I am still struggling to tell the truth against what I would call reprisals.'' A space-based system of X-ray laser beams, powered by nuclear detonations, is no longer viewed as the centerpiece of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s proposed Strategic Defense Initiative, known as SDI or Star Wars SDI research now focuses on land-based weapons to defend the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> against <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> nuclear missiles, <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said.
