<FIRST>r a BC-Theater     07-15 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Much Ado About Nothing' Starring Kevin Kline Opens in Central
Park</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` A merry war'' is the way one character describes the relationship between <PERSON> Benedick </PERSON> and <PERSON> Beatrice </PERSON>, those tempest-tossed, tart-tongued lovers in `` Much Ado About Nothing.'' That's pretty much the way it's played in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> where the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Shakespeare Festival opened its boisterous revival of one of <PERSON> Shakespeare </PERSON>'s most durable comedies on Thursday night. Director <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Freedman </PERSON> opts for the robust rather than the romantic in his staging of the play, an approach that accentuates the laughs rather than the poetry. Fortunately, he gets both from <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Kline </PERSON>, who probably could walk on water if asked to do so by his director. <PERSON> Kline </PERSON> does just about everything else in `` Much Ado,'' and he accomplishes it with such style, wit and grace that he gives hamminess a good name. The actor makes a first-rate arrogant, foolish and finally lovestruck <PERSON> Benedick </PERSON>. Consider <PERSON> Kline </PERSON>'s entrance in the play. It's no quiet walk-on. It's a full-fledged sword fight, staged with an alarming athleticism by fight director B.H. <PERSON> Barry </PERSON>. In the middle of this ruckus, <PERSON> Beatrice </PERSON> sits quietly and reads a book. The battle lines are drawn as soon as the play begins. If <PERSON> Blythe </PERSON> <PERSON> Danner </PERSON>, who appears as the equally obstinate and egocentric <PERSON> Beatrice </PERSON>, ca n't match the <PERSON> Kline </PERSON> juggernaut, she gives it a good try. Her Beatrice is too much of a lady, and her odd, almost squeaky voice is not particularly suited for <PERSON> Shakespeare </PERSON>. Still, she exudes an impertinence that mangages to charm <PERSON> Benedick </PERSON> and the audience by the end of the evening. A special joy of <PERSON> Freedman </PERSON>'s production is the strong supporting cast which usually fades into the background. <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> makes a comical yet touching <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON>, the nobleman who instigates the matching up of <PERSON> Benedick </PERSON> with <PERSON> Beatrice </PERSON> and <PERSON> Claudio </PERSON> with Hero. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON>, the melancholy villain of the play, is a strange character. He sets in motion a subplot to besmirch Hero's honor and then disappears. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> does a fine comic turn _ all smirks and sneers _ and remains in one's memory even after he leaves the stage. There is more good support from <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerringer </PERSON> as <PERSON> Leonato </PERSON>, <PERSON> Beatrice </PERSON>'s uncle, another of those underrated roles, and from <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Stiller </PERSON> as the dumbest of Dogberrys. Because <PERSON> Beatrice </PERSON> and <PERSON> Benedick </PERSON> are so strong, the actors playing the other set of lovers tend to disappear into the plot. That's the case with <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON>, a colorless <PERSON> Claudio </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Phoebe </PERSON> <PERSON> Cates </PERSON>, a one-dimensional Hero. Designer <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Ezell </PERSON> has provided a fairy tale 19th century Italian town, which is where <PERSON> Freedman </PERSON> sets the play. The costumes by <PERSON> Theoni </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Aldredge </PERSON> are colorful and apppropriate to the period. There is an inevitable falloff after the exuberant first act. But that's because the ending has been telegraphed long before the play is over and the involved plot convolutions must be straightened out before the curtain falls. Still this `` Much Ado About Nothing'' spins gaily for much of the evening and most of it turns because of the whirlwind performance of <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Kline </PERSON>. He makes it the airiest, most bouyant production in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
