<HEAD>Tiny Cracks Found In Nearly Half Of Inspected Boeing 737s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tiny cracks were found in nearly half the aging <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737 jetliners known to have been inspected since the top ripped off an <ORGANIZATION> Aloha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> 737 in late May, a <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> official testified Thursday. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, manager of the airframe branch in the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> aircraft certification office, described the initial responses to an <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> `` airworthiness directive'' in testimony to a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> hearing on the accident The order, issued within a week after the April 28 accident, required all <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737s with 30,000 or more landings to undergo a special visual inspection of fuselage lap joints, or areas where parts of the fuselage are bonded and riveted together. The directive ordered those with more than 50,000 landings to have additional inspections using high-frequency electronic equipment. Airlines were required to fix any problems found and to report the results to the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>. A flight attendant was killed and 61 persons injured when a portion of the fuselage on a <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737 peeled off during an <LOCATION> Aloha </LOCATION> flight from <LOCATION> Hilo </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION>, exposing the first-class section to the open air at 24,000 feet. The pilot and co-pilot managed to land the crippled jet 13 minutes later in <LOCATION> Maui </LOCATION> although one of the two engines quit. <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> said 291 737s were affected by the inspection order issued shortly after the accident. As of this week, he said, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> has received reports on 100 planes, of which 49 reported cracks. The largest crack found was about one-half inch, but most were three-eighths of an inch or smaller, he said. The most found in one plane were 31 cracks within a 40-inch space. Five or more cracks were found in 14 of the planes, he said. Cracks can occur around the rivets used to join the panels. <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> said none of the cracks reported had joined up _ `` In other words, they had not gone from fastener to fastener.'' <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Gamble </PERSON> declined comment on the cracks until he had spoken with the airlplane manufacturer's engineers. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashworth </PERSON>, manager of the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> aircraft certification division, said he was concerned about the cracks but saw no imminent danger to the planes or to air passengers. As of today `` we have not seen evidence of impending failure in any airplane. We of course are requiring that all cracks we finds be repaired. That's only prudent maintenance,'' he said. In testimony earlier Thursday, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Oldani </PERSON> said he was shocked to learn in an October 1987 meeting with <LOCATION> Aloha </LOCATION> officials that the airline did not have a specific program to prevent corrosion of its air fleet. <PERSON> Oldani </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> that <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Arii </PERSON>, <PERSON> Aloha </PERSON>'s staff vice president of quality control and engineering, told him that <PERSON> Aloha </PERSON> had stopped its corrosion control program three years earlier. Much of the testimony at the hearing has focused on technical studies of how cracks form in 737s. The inquiry is trying to determine the cause of the <LOCATION> Aloha </LOCATION> accident, but early investigations have focused on possible structural failure, perhaps aggravated by corrosion. <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> told the panel that the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> was formulating `` very demanding'' new rules to require extensive inspections of early 737s.
</TEXT>
