<HEAD>Cemetery Yields Skeletons From Argentina's `Dirty War'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDALL HACKLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AVELLANEDA, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Eleven of the skeletons each had a bullet hole in the skull, some with mouths agape as if in a shriek. A few still had on shreds of the clothing they wore in their last living moment. In a walled-off, tennis-court-sized section of <ORGANIZATION> Avellaneda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Municipal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cemetery </ORGANIZATION> is a burial ground that authorities believe contains the remains of 200 to 300 victims of <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s `` dirty war'' of the 1970s, when a military dictatorship ruled <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>. The mass gravesite in this industrial city of 650,000 southeast of <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION> is the largest so far found of those believed slain by 1970s security forces hunting down `` subversives.'' Each weekday, six young forensic anthropologists unearth more bones in an attempt to document what happened to those victims, 95 percent of whom bear evidence of having been shot in the head from short-range at the peak of the repression in 1976-78. `` Most of the victims are of our own generation,'' said the team's leader, 30-year-old <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> <PERSON> Tidball </PERSON> <PERSON> Binz </PERSON>. `` We even found the remains of one woman who was 76. It's hard to figure out who she was a threat to.'' The four men and two women of the <ORGANIZATION> Argentine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forensic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Anthropology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Team </ORGANIZATION> have uncovered 83 victims in the four years they've been working together. Through identifications of 20 of those victims, three military officers have been convicted of homicide or kidnapping. A government panel created by President <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> identified 8,961 people who died during those years, although human rights groups say the number who were abducted, vanished and now are presumed dead is about 20,000. Building legal cases against the killers is one of the goals of the team. Another is documenting what happened in those bloody years when scores of suspected leftists _ data shows half were laborers or students _ `` disappeared,'' most at night, and most from their own homes. Most were taken by security men to one of the 340 detention centers for questioning; many were tortured, often fatally. Evidence indicates some were dumped from airplanes into the River Plate estuary. Others were tossed in unmarked graves that came to be called `` NN,'' or no-name graves. `` It's not pretty,'' said <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Fondebrider </PERSON>, at 24 the youngest member of the team. `` We're trying to piece together what happened for history's sake so that hopefully it will never occur again.'' The team has no government funding, a surprise considering that <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>, a civilian who took over the presidency after the military stepped down, is a human rights activist who ordered trials that convicted five military junta leaders, including two ex-presidents. The team receives $ 48,000 in funding from the New York-based <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Mitterrand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> France </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> of Churches. Its members take public transportation to work and share office space with a human rights group in an old three-story building near downtown <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION>. The team began in 1984 when <PERSON> Tidball </PERSON> <PERSON> Binz </PERSON>, then a medical student, was recruited by the renowned forensic anthropologist Clyde Snow of <LOCATION> Norman </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Okla. </LOCATION>, to help the newly restored democracy identify the remains of some dirty-war victims. Five of <PERSON> Tidball </PERSON> <PERSON> Binz </PERSON>'s companions joined the team. Its work involves meticulously excavating a skeleton, measuring bones, making X-rays, examining dental records and comparing every bit to information from the medical charts of the missing. Their findings are entered into a computer. Finding one that matches dental records often horrifies the victim's relatives. `` It is still very, very traumatic for the families of the victims. Some even continue denying it -LRB- the body -RRB- is who it is despite the proof,'' <PERSON> Tidball </PERSON> <PERSON> Binz </PERSON> said. What's found in the graves, which Snow calls `` a time capsule that preserves proof of the identity and cause of death,'' have proven damning to those who contended the victims died in gunfights with security forces. In nearly every case uncovered by the team, evidence showed they had been slain with a shot to the base of the skull from about three feet away. In many cases, fragments of bullets from standard police-issue shotguns were found in the skull, <PERSON> Tidball </PERSON> <PERSON> Binz </PERSON> said. A few cases showed victims were pregnant or recently gave birth. Some burial plots contained groupings of chopped-off hands.
</TEXT>
