<HEAD>New Production of ``Ring'' Cycle Highlights Beyreuth Festival</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN FISCHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAYREUTH, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mix an experimental director from communist <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> with <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON>'s legendary operas, and you come up with one of the most eagerly awaited <LOCATION> Bayreuth </LOCATION> seasons in years. A new production of <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON>'s epic `` Ring'' cycle under East German director <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kupfer </PERSON> and celebrated <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> conductor <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Barenboim </PERSON>, will be the centerpiece of <LOCATION> Bayreuth </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Richard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wagner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Festival </ORGANIZATION>, which opens on July 26. `` From <PERSON> Kupfer </PERSON> one can expect a modern, perhaps even socially critical production,'' critic <PERSON> Gerhard </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Frankfurter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Allegemeine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zeitung </ORGANIZATION> newspaper said in an interview. `` The story of the family tragedy and its elements of greed, particularly in ` Die Walkuere,' lends itself well to a socially critical interpretation.'' The new `` Ring'' production is clearly the highlight of the season. Previous festival `` Ring'' productions have set the old Germanic myths in various time periods, and in styles ranging from bombastic to relatively spare and modern. The festival, first held in 1876, transforms the placid northern Bavarian town of <LOCATION> Bayreuth </LOCATION> for one month every summer into a gathering place for <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> lovers across the world. For nearly 40 years, <PERSON> Wolfgang </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON>, the composer's grandson, has been running the festival, occasionally also producing festival performances. Performances regularly sell out way ahead of time, as there are only 1,925 seats available in the theater <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> built specifically for his works. The theater was financed by <LOCATION> Bavaria </LOCATION>'s King <PERSON> Ludwig </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, nicknamed `` Mad King <PERSON> Ludwig </PERSON>'' because of his extreme shyness and love of overspending on elaborate, Disneyland-like castles. According to <PERSON> Mathias </PERSON> <PERSON> Vogt </PERSON>, a spokesman for the festival, this year was no exception to the festival's sell-out tradition. `` Demand for the festival was greater this year than ever,'' he said. `` Tickets sold out shortly after going on sale last November.'' The festival will open with the return of last year's `` Parsifal,'' directed by <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedrich </PERSON> and conducted by <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Levine </PERSON> `` My favorite opera is ` Parsifal' and that's why I'm really looking forward to going,'' said <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> fan <PERSON> Manfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Schuldt </PERSON>, 34, of <LOCATION> Hamburg </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Schuldt </PERSON> has been making the annual trek to <LOCATION> Bayreuth </LOCATION> for the last 10 years. `` But it's the new ` Ring' production that's causing the most excitement,'' he said. `` <PERSON> Barenboim </PERSON> has a special style. You really notice when he's conducting.'' <PERSON> Barenboim </PERSON>, musical director of the renowned <ORGANIZATION> Orchestre </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paris </ORGANIZATION>, will conduct the four works comprising the mighty `` Der Ring des <PERSON> Nibelungen </PERSON>'' cycle to begin on July 27 with `` Das Rheingold.'' The other works, `` Die Walkuere,'' `` Siegfried'' and `` Goetterdaemmerung'' will follow. Opera lovers also say they are eager to see what East German director <PERSON> Kupfer </PERSON> does with the new `` Ring'' production. `` That's the sensation of the season to me,'' <PERSON> August </PERSON> <PERSON> Everding </PERSON>, general director of the Bayerischen Staatstheater -LRB- Bavarian State Theater -RRB- said. `` <PERSON> Kupfer </PERSON> is a wonderful opera director.'' Critic <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> looked to <PERSON> Kupfer </PERSON>'s 1978 <LOCATION> Bayreuth </LOCATION> production of `` The Flying Dutchman'' as a clue to what audiences might expect this summer. `` It was highly imaginative, but critical at the same time,'' he said. `` <PERSON> Kupfer </PERSON> manages to bring current aspects into his work, and audiences today can easily identify with it.'' Other festival presentations will be a return of last year's romantic opera, `` Lohengrin'' and `` Die Meistersinger von <LOCATION> Nuernberg </LOCATION>. Opera singers in this year's festival include some of <LOCATION> Bayreuth </LOCATION> favorites such as <LOCATION> Siegfried </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> as Parsifal and <PERSON> Siegfried </PERSON>, <PERSON> Franz </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazura </PERSON> as Klingsor and the Wanderer, and <PERSON> Waltraud </PERSON> <PERSON> Meier </PERSON> as <PERSON> Kundry </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Waltraute </LOCATION>. Among those appearing in <LOCATION> Bayreuth </LOCATION> for the first time include <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Opie </PERSON>, <PERSON> Marie-Claire </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Reirdan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>. There will be a total of 30 performances at the festival, which runs until Aug. 29. Meanwhile, <LOCATION> Bayreuth </LOCATION> tourist officials laugh at some aspects of the summer invasion. `` We get people writing letters to the mayor asking for tickets,'' <ORGANIZATION> Bayreuth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tourist </ORGANIZATION> director <PERSON> Jo </PERSON> <PERSON> Schumacher </PERSON> said. `` And lots of tourists just stumble in here casually and are astounded when they ca n't get tickets.'' <LOCATION> Bayreuth </LOCATION>, a picturesque town founded in the 12th century, also shows a number of art exhibits during the <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> festival, much of them <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> related.
