<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Banks have raised their prime lending rate to 9.5 percent from 9 percent, pushing the benchmark interest rate to the highest level in more than two years. Thursday's increase reflected a rise in the banks' own borrowing costs and signaled more expensive loans for consumers and businesses. It marked the second time this year the nation's banks have raised the prime, which is used to calculate a range of fixed and adjustable-rate corporate and consumer loans.
</TEXT>
