<FIRST>r f PM-Cosmetics-Business Bjt   07-15 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cosmetics-Business, Bjt,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cosmetics: Lucre, Snob Appeal and Fame</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Cosmetics, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It is no accident that many department stores put their cosmetics counters just inside the front door, the area with the highest customer traffic. When <PERSON> Bloomingdale </PERSON>'s redid the first floor of its flagship <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> store a few years ago, the centerpiece was the makeup and perfume department. It also is no accident that the front pages of women's magazines often are dominated by ads for <ORGANIZATION> Revlon </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Estee </PERSON> <PERSON> Lauder </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Clairol </ORGANIZATION>, Coty and other big names in beauty, while inside, articles dispense tips on how women can totally make themselves over. Cosmetics is a big and lucrative business, bringing in $ 17 billion in sales last year. The world's largest cosmetic company, <ORGANIZATION> Avon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, had 1987 sales of nearly $ 1.81 billion from its cosmetics, fragrances and toiletries business. That produced a $ 251.3 million pre-tax profit. Numbers like that make successful cosmetic companies desirable properties. <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Perelman </PERSON> battled for three months in 1985 before finally winning a $ 1.65 billion takeover fight for <ORGANIZATION> Revlon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, one of the world's top cosmetic manufacturers. The profitable business lately has come under scrutiny by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, too. The House small business panel on Wednesday held a hearing to examine health and safety questions about cosmetics, some of which are said to contain chemicals that could cause cancer, birth defects, central nervous disorders, skin and eye irritations and allergic reactions. Cosmetics are profitable because they are relatively inexpensive to produce and their prices can be marked up heavily because of snob appeal. The cosmetic industry has its own equivalent of designer fashions. For example, a mascara by <ORGANIZATION> Maybelline </ORGANIZATION> was priced at $ 3 in a <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> drug store, while a similar Estee Lauder product sold for $ 10 at <ORGANIZATION> Saks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fifth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Avenue </ORGANIZATION>. Manufacturers and retailers both are big beneficiaries of makeup's high profit margins. `` If you pay $ 10 for an item, the manufacturer probably gets $ 6,'' leaving $ 4 for the retailer, said <ORGANIZATION> Diana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION>, a cosmetic industry analyst for the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Salomon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. One reason why retailers do so well from makeup is that at bigger department and specialty stores, such as <ORGANIZATION> Bloomingdale </ORGANIZATION>'s, <LOCATION> Marshall </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION>'s, <ORGANIZATION> Nordstrom </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Macy </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION>, the people selling the cosmetics often are paid at least in part by the manufacturer, Ms. <PERSON> Temple </PERSON> said In shopping for cosmetics, women generally are motivated by price and the image created for the product by ad campaigns. But if you put the Maybelline mascara and the <PERSON> Estee </PERSON> <PERSON> Lauder </PERSON> item side by side, is there any difference between the ingredients of the two? `` Not a heck of a lot,'' said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Salzman </PERSON>, an analyst with the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Goldman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sachs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` There are differences in quality but the differences in price are greater,'' Ms. <PERSON> Temple </PERSON> said. Cosmetics sell because they can make women more glamorous. But they also have given the people associated with the industry their own special aura. The late <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Revson </PERSON>, one of the founders of <ORGANIZATION> Revlon </ORGANIZATION>, was constantly in the society pages. And actress <PERSON> Lauren </PERSON> <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> made it into the movies after her impeccably made-up face appeared in many a <ORGANIZATION> Revlon </ORGANIZATION> ad.
