<FIRST>r f PM-TelephoneAds Bjt   07-15 0657</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Telephone Ads, Bjt,0679</SECOND>
<HEAD>Long-Distance Commercials Take Lighter Approach</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 You can quit cringing at the first sight of those long-distance telephone commercials: telephone admakers plan to lighten up. <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T is winding down its use of ads that show corporate underlings getting chewed out by the boss _ or worrying that they might be fired _ for picking the wrong telephone service. Instead, it is phasing in new ads that show its employees describing how they can help your business. Competitor <ORGANIZATION> US </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sprint </ORGANIZATION>, meanwhile, plans to begin using a new series of ads next week that indirectly pokes fun at <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T's old approach as it humorously demonstrates how important it is to get a clear line when you want to place a business call. The ads were directed by <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Sedelmaier </PERSON>, best known for his `` Where's the Beef'' ads for <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON>'s and his fast-talker spots for <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION>. In one new Sprint ad, four men are in an office waiting for the boss's call. `` That's him,'' they say as the phone rings. But as the camera catches every expressive twitch of the face of the guy who picks up the phone, the boss' instructions are reduced to gibberish because of the poor quality of the phone line. `` Listen carefully.. 500 cases.. by Monday ... we'll lose the account'' are some of the fragments that can be After the boss hangs up, the man who took the call dutifully repeats for the others exactly what he heard. The message is that this wo n't happen if you use Sprint. But there is no suggestion that somebody is about to lose his job over it. Sprint executives and their admakers at <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION>