<HEAD>Analysts: Rematch Would Give Coniston New Life</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A court-ordered rematch of the proxy fight beween <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> would be unprecedented and would strengthen the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> partnership's attempt to control the personal care giant, according to industry analysts. A federal judge said Wednesday he was inclined to order a new proxy vote in the six-month battle because <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> misled stockholders about <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> before the election. Analysts said institutional investors, seeking a quick profit from the personal care giant, probably own more <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> stock than before the April vote and would be more likely to back <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION>'s dissident slate of board candidates <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> controls about 5.8 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION>'s common shares outstanding. The partnership wants to win board seats to pressure the 12-member <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> board to sell the company, which <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> believes would boost the value of its stock. `` I think it's safe to assume that there are more arbitragers holding <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> today than back in March,'' said <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> <PERSON> Upham </PERSON>. `` I think that <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> is definitely viewed as a speculative plot.'' Judges in the past have ordered new proxy votes, but that typically has been in cases involving huge vote discrepancies where a new vote was deemed irrelevant. The <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> case is rarer because it involves information a judge determined could have affected the outcome. `` The court found that there was something misleading,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Todd </PERSON> <PERSON> Lang </PERSON>, a partner with the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> law firm <ORGANIZATION> Weil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gotschal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Manges. `` This does n't happen very often. Usually when you have a challenge it's a challenge to the tally.'' In the April 21 election, <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION>'s 27,000 shareholders rejected <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION>'s slate of four candidates to the board by 52 percent to 48 percent proportion. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> said at Wednesday's hearing that he was inclined to order a new election because `` the essence of the election was tainted in a material way.'' Last week, <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> ruled <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> misled stockholders about <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> in newspaper advertisements leading up to the proxy vote. He also said a failure by Boston-based <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> to disclose a series of standstill agreements with potential suitors was not misleading and would not have affected the election. <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> scheduled a trial the week of Aug. 22 on <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION>'s charges that <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> violated federal securities laws by failing to disclose the limited partners in RB Partners, a <LOCATION> Bahamian </LOCATION> company formed to buy <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> stock. The judge said Wednesday that regardless of his ruling in the second phase of the case, he is likely to order the new vote. <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> has asked for a new election of eight directors in the fall, pre-empting <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION>'s normal spring meeting. <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> principal <PERSON> Augustus </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> said stockholders would consider the standstill agreements _ under which 10 companies agreed not to attempt to buy <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> for two years ending in November _ if <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> orders a new election. `` I think there's a totally new mix of information available to stockholders,'' <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> said. `` We'll just have to see next time around whether that's enough to change things.'' <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> sued <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> in April, alleging the securities law violations. The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> investment firm responded with its claim of misrepresentation. The counterclaim was heard in court first because Judge <PERSON> Rya </PERSON> <PERSON> Zobel </PERSON>, then handling the case, felt that if <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> lost its challenge to the proxy vote then <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION>'s case would be moot. `` The judge indicated he was still evolving his thinking and he has n't come up with a remedy yet,'' <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Fausch </PERSON> said. `` One of the remedies that is possible is a new election. Let's take that at face value.''
