<HEAD>Farmers Welcomes Oregon Rejection Of Hostile Takeover Proposal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The head of <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> says a hostile takeover attempt of the company by a British conglomerate should be dropped following the rejection of the plan by <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>'s insurance commissioner. <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, Ky.-based subsidiary of the British B.A.T. <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, has offered $ 4.5 billion for the Los Angeles-based Farmers. Farmers directors rejected the proposal. Oregon Insurance Commissioner <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Kulongoski </PERSON> concluded on Thursday that the proposed buyout of <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> would adversely affect Farmers' policyholders and competition in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>'s insurance trade. <PERSON> Kulongoski </PERSON> cited the intention of <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION>, which owns a major tobacco company, to restrict the non-smoker policies sold by Farmers. `` Director <PERSON> Kulongoski </PERSON>'s decision on this matter confirms our belief that this proposed transaction would ultimately be detrimental to Farmers and its <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> policyholders,'' said <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Denlea </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, Farmers' chairman. <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement it was `` completely astonished'' by the decision. `` A cursory reading of the decision strongly suggests that the commissioner has reached conclusions that are contrary to law and appear to be unsupported by the record and the facts,'' a spokesman said. <PERSON> Kulongoski </PERSON>'s order can be appealed to the courts. The takeover bid as now structured would require approval of insurance regulators in nine states. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s insurance commissioner also has rejected the proposal, and <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> has approved it. `` Following the recent decision by the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION>, this is a second very significant setback to <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION>' unwanted hostile takeover attempt,'' <PERSON> Denlea </PERSON> said `` We believe that <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION> will face further regulatory difficulties in current and pending reviews by other state insurance departments.'' <PERSON> Kulongoski </PERSON>, citing his role as hearings officer in the case, made only limited remarks outside his statements in the order. He said the case is unique in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> insurance history because it does not involve a troubled insurer being acquired by a more financially sound company. `` Rather, it is the proposed acquisition of a very well-managed company by a larger company seeking to diversify into the financial services market in this country,'' <PERSON> Kulongoski </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION>' statement also took issue with <PERSON> Kulongoski </PERSON>'s characterization of Farmers as well-managed The `` statement to the effect that this is not a financially distressed company, but rather a well-managed one being acquired by a larger company seeking to diversify, suggests that the decision is anti-takeover, rather than protection for the policyholders,'' the statement said. The commissioner in his ruling said the proposed acquisition `` subjects policyholders and shareholders to substantial risks while providing no benefit that Farmers does not already enjoy.'' He also said the continued denials by B.A.T. and <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION> `` of the known adverse health effects of tobacco smoking, and its stated intentions of precluding Farmers from referring to such health effects in its marketing literature, do not promote the interest of the insurance-buying public.'' <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION> owns <ORGANIZATION> Brown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Williamson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tobacco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> along with retail concerns including <ORGANIZATION> Saks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fifth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Avenue </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Marshall </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION>'s.
