<HEAD>Macmillan To Appeal Injunction Ruling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said it would appeal a judge's ruling that blocks the publishing giant from proceeding with a massive massive restructuring designed to thwart an unwanted bid from the <ORGANIZATION> Robert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bass </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> After nearly five weeks of consideration, <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chancery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday issued a 58-page opinion granting <PERSON> Bass </PERSON>'s request for a preliminary injunction that effectively blocks the restructuring. <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON> said in a statement that it was taking an expedited appeal to the <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in an effort to reverse the decision. An unidentified <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON> spokesman said in the statement that <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON>' ruling was `` erroneous as a matter of law'' and that <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON> was confident of succeeding on appeal. The ruling came after the close of the stock market. But in trading on te <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> fell 50 cents to $ 74 on Thursday. <PERSON> Josy </PERSON> <PERSON> Ingersoll </PERSON>, an attorney representing the Texas-based Bass group, had no comment on whether <PERSON> Bass </PERSON> would proceed with a tender offer. The group previously had said it would launch a tender offer upon granting of a preliminary injunction. `` There's no action to prevent anybody from doing a tender offer,'' she said. The Bass group also has said it has the necessary financing to complete its $ 1.9 billion buyout. Bass originally offered to acquire <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON> for $ 64 a share in May, but raised his bid to $ 73 a share, or about $ 1.9 billion for the 90.1 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> shares the group does not already own after the publisher unveiled its restructuring plan. <PERSON> Ingersoll </PERSON> said the judge found that <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON>'s attempt to restructure was an unreasonable response to <PERSON> Bass </PERSON>'s takeover proposal. Based on legal precedents, `` when a board does something in reaction to an offer for the company, there has to be a threat ... and there was n't a threat'' in this case, she said from her <LOCATION> Wilmington </LOCATION>, Del. office. Bass had charged that <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON>'s restructuring, which would have separated the company's information services and publishing operations into two separate, publicly traded companies, was inadequate and misleading. The group also charged that the plan would have transferred control to four top <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON> executives for a cheap price. In rejecting <PERSON> Bass </PERSON>'s buyout offer as well as a counter proposal to restructure the company, <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> repeatedly said its own plan was in the best interest of shareholders. <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON> was just hours away from beginning its restructuring, which included paying shareholders a special $ 52.35-a-share dividend, when <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON> issued a temporary restraining order on June 10. <PERSON> Bass </PERSON>'s restructuring plan would pay shareholders a dividend of $ 58 per share.
