<FIRST>r f BC-Japan-Labor     07-15 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-Labor,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Calls For Improved Working, Living Conditions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A government report, noting that Japanese work longer than people in other industrialized nations but have less buying power, calls for improved working and living conditions in this country. The report, issued by the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> Friday, urged shorter work weeks, lower consumer prices, more housing land and cheaper housing. The report said Japanese worked an average 2,150 hours in 1986, the last year for which such statistics were available, compared to 1,938 hours for Britons, 1,924 hours for Americans, 1,655 hours for West Germans and 1,643 hours for the French, said <PERSON> Atsuko </PERSON> <PERSON> Ishii </PERSON> of the ministry's Labor Affairs Division. Of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s total workforce of 60.8 million, 59.11 were employed in 1987, for an unemployment rate of 2.8 percent compared to 6.2 percent in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, 7.9 percent in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, 10.4 percent in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and 10.6 percent in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, according to Miss <PERSON> Ishii </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> calculates its unemployment rate differently from other Western countries, counting its armed forces and those who work as little as one hour a month. Japanese officials say <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s official rate would be about double if it were calculated by Western methods. Women accounted for 36.5 percent of the work force last year, the report said. The average worker's annual salary in 1987 was 4.99 million yen, or $ 38,380, including summer and winter bonuses, Miss <PERSON> Ishii </PERSON> quoted the report as saying. Workers in primary industry _ farming, forestry, fishing and mining _ numbered 5.41 million, or 9.3 percent of all workers, in 1985, the most recent year for which statistics were available, she said. In the secondary or manufacturing industry, there were 19.33 million workers, or 33.1 percent of the working population. The largest number of workers in 1985 were 33.44 million in tertiary industry, defined as power and water supply, transport, communications, sales, food, financial, real estate and public sectors, the report said. They represented 53.7 percent of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s working population that year, Miss <PERSON> Ishii </PERSON> said The report noted 18.9 percent of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s workforce was older than 55 last year, as opposed to 12.9 percent in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and 10.2 percent in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
