 Grain and soybean futures opened lower but quickly turned mixed in volatile activity today on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>. Analysts attributed the lower opening to a continuation of the profit-taking that surfaced late in Thursday's session following two days of sharply higher prices. Forecasts for another month of hot, dry weather in the parched Corn Belt provided incentive for traders to bid prices higher this morning but uncertainty about the prospects for rain next week added an element of edginess to the markets, analysts said, `` People are not sure we're not going to get another rain front in the middle of next week and the markets are very, very nervous,'' said <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>, grain specialist in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. In early trading, wheat was 3 cents to 7 cents higher with the contract for delivery in July at $ 3.91 a bushel; corn was 3 -LCB- cents lower to 1 -RCB- cents higher with July at $ 3.36 a bushel; oats were 1 cent lower to 3 cents higher with July at $ 3.07 a bushel; soybeans were unchanged to 15 -LCB- cents higher with July at $ 9.81 a bushel. Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle were .20 cent lower to .25 cent higher with August at 64.35 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .85 cent higher with August at 74.65 cents a pound; hogs were .27 cent lower to .65 cent higher with July at 45.77 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .80 cent to 1.40 cents higher with July at 36.70 cents a pound. Livestock and meat futures settled mostly h