<HEAD>Icahn Can Sell Texaco Stock Soon _ But Will He?</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY30</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Like a casino player fingering the chips in his pocket, corporate raider <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> is likely to wait awhile before he walks up to the window and cashes in his <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> stock for a multimillion-dollar prize. The beleagured oil giant's largest shareholder and most vocal critic is just days away from being able to sell his roughly 36 million shares and keep the profits. But will he? Speaking from his new offices in <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kisco </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> said that `` at this point we have n't made any decision yet'' about the 14.8 percent <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> stake. He noted there is `` a myriad of possibilities _ including doing nothing _ and we've made no determination of what we're going to do.'' Under the `` short-swing'' profit rule, a holder of more than 5 percent of a company's stock must keep those shares for at least six months, otherwise any profits revert back to the company. That period ends Wednesday for <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> stock traded at just over $ 45 a share on Friday. At that price, <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> has a paper profit of about $ 410 million, based on his average purchase price of $ 34 a share. Wall Streeters agree <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> is least likely to just dump the shares on the open market, considering the depressing effect such a move would have on <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s stock price. `` The bottom line is that neither <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> nor <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> want to see the shares go down,'' said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Ting </PERSON>, an analyst at the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Oppenheimer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Far more handsome would be the sale of <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>'s shares in a block to a third party willing to pay a heftier price At $ 60 a share, the price <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> put on the table in his proposed $ 14 billion-plus buyout, he would reap nearly a billion in profits. <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> would not comment on whether he had spoken recently with <ORGANIZATION> Husky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> or <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, two companies with whom he once discussed a joint <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> bid. `` It's impossible to know if he is under pressure to liquidate something,'' said <PERSON> Rosario </PERSON> <PERSON> Ilacqua </PERSON>, a vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` But if he believes the assets are worth $ 70 to $ 80 a share, why would he sell at $ 46? When asked whether <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> had been in contact with <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> regarding the disposition of his holdings, a spokeswoman said the <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, N.Y.-based company `` does not comment on the activities of our shareholders.'' But a source close to the company said, `` Obviously -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- is concerned about <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>, they know that he is not someone you take lightly.'' `` I would assume <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> management would like to get him out, and get their stock up in the $ 50s,'' <PERSON> Ilacqua </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>'s concession of defeat in a heated proxy contest for five seats on <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s board does not put the oil giant's managment in the clear. Some experts speculate <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> might be waiting to see just how close he came in the battle, which took place last month at the company's annual meeting. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> has said it would take between three and four weeks for an official tally, and results are expected soon. <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>, who also heads <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, was dealt what might have been a fatal blow in the fight by the aggressive leveraged buyout firm <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roberts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which voted its 4.9 percent stake for <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> management. In conceding defeat shortly after <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION>'s announcement, <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> called the company's stake the swing vote. But analysts are not so sure. One suggested <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>'s losing margin may have been far wider than he has let on. `` If it had been a close call, he would n't have conceded defeat,'' said one analyst who asked not to be quoted by name. `` His nature is being a battler, stubborn and persistent.'' Meanwhile, <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> is knee-deep in its own restructuring, which includes a $ 3 billion payment to <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> to settle a lawsuit resulting from <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s 1984 acquisition of <ORGANIZATION> Getty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> after <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> had made earlier moves to acquire <PERSON> Getty </PERSON>. In addition, <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> has begun selling off up to $ 5 billion worth of marginally profitable assets and say