<HEAD>Stock Prices Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prices finished marginally lower Friday on <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> as the market was stumped by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade figures. The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index finished the session off 1.8 points, or 0.1 percent, at 1,861.5. Trading volume was a healthy 591.5 million shares, compared with Thursday's 526.6 million shares. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> merchandise trade deficit widened to $ 10.9 billion in May from a revised $ 10.3 billion shortfall in April. But the latest deficit came well within the expected range. `` We would've known what to do had it been high or low, but when the figures came in close to home, we did n't know what to do with it,'' one equity salesman said. <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Davies </PERSON>, an equity analyst at <ORGANIZATION> CL-Alexanders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cruickshank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, said the trade figures amounted to `` damp fireworks'' for equities. `` Financial markets are beginning to prepare themselves for another interest rate hike,'' <PERSON> Davies </PERSON> said. A government report that <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s retail price index rose 0.4 percent in June compared with May and was up 4.6 percent from June 1987, heightened suspicions that British interest rates might be headed higher. `` People are definitely concerned about higher interest rates,'' one analyst said.
