<FIRST>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv15   07-15 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 15,0701</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 15</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Friday, July 15</NOTE>
<HEAD>Consumer Attitudes, The Best Bet Against Inflation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Everyone is worrying about inflation, but a lot of folks are doing something about it, and they just might have the final say. Those folks are consumers, and they have been resisting price increases for several years now and seem intent on continuing their vigilance. This is n't an assumption; the activity shows up in official statistics. The measurements that prove the case are the gross national product implicit price deflator and the gross national product fixed-weight price index. For practical purposes, the important thing to remember about the fixed-weight price index is that it measures only changes in prices, and these prices are of the same products month after month. The implicit price deflator is a bit more sophisticated, measuring not just prices but changes in the composition of purchases. It has been rising much more slowly than its more rigid cousin. The importance of this disparity is that it indicates a resistance to price increases by consumers. They have continued to buy, but they have avoided items rising in price and, when possible, switched to more stable items. Such behavior is enormously significant, suggesting a fundamental change in consumer attitudes from earlier periods. An analysis by <ORGANIZATION> Wright </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> contrasts this price resistance to the attitude that prevailed during much of the 1960s and 1970s, when consumers simply went ahead and bought. In fact, many consumers bought more than they needed at any given time, convinced that future prices would be even higher. Those were very different times. Consumers were fatalistic, convinced that they could have little impact on pricing factors. Why try to hold down the budget when <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> was forcing up gasoline and heating oil prices? But there was more to it than that. Many workers had broad cost-of-living increases built into union contracts, enabling them to offset higher prices. Industry's attitude toward wage increases was simply to give in and then raise prices. And, for reasons not explained logically, there existed a feeling that inflation was a way of life that could n't be disciplined. In those days, the two indicators of inflation rose in relation to each other. It was only in the 1980s that they began to diverge, indicating that consumers felt they could do something about pricing, such as declining to buy. This relatively new sense of consumer power is especially noticeable in automobile sales, which for several years have relied on incentives. Take away those incentives and sales dive; replace them and they rise again. It has occurred in housing sales as well, as many would-be sellers in some of the more affluent neighborhoods have discovered over the past few months. Houses that a year ago sold within days of listing, now remain on the market for months, even though mortgages have been relatively easy to obtain. Some retailers are complaining, but in view of today's consumer attitude you might say they should have known better. Early this year apparel prices rose sharply, followed quickly by sales problems for many apparel retailers. The new attitude has n't been lost on producers of services and manufactured goods, many of whom have chosen to absorb higher costs in order to maintain sales, rather than pass on increases and lose customer loyalty. The resistance applies even to interest rates. Strange as it sounds to some folks who could n't get an appointment with a bank loan officer a few years ago, many banks now advertise for customers, especially for home loans. The new attitude can be found in, of all places, wage settlements. Learning from the 1970s, when wage increases were more than offset by price increases, workers have been seeking less, opting instead for wage-price stability. It is encouraging news, this inflation fight by a lot of ordinary folks. Together, they make an anti-inflation force as strong as almost any other, perhaps even matching the vaunted power of the August <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Friday, July 15.</NOTE>
</DOC>
