<HEAD>Producers Say Steel Imports Surged in May</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Steel imports surged in May to their highest level since July 1986, domestic producers said Friday. An importers association, interpreting the same <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> data, said, however, that imports, excluding semi-finished metal bound for processing on <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> mills, were held within the limits of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> steel quota system for the first five months of the year. May imports totaled 1.94 million tons, compared with 1.53 million tons in April and 1.85 million tons in May 1987, according to the American Iron and <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. Imports of all steel products, including semi-finshed ordered by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> producers, totaled 9.05 million tons, up from 8.4 million tons in the comparable 1987 period, the Washington-based <ORGANIZATION> AISI </ORGANIZATION> said. `` These figures reinforce the domestic industry's assertion that the system of voluntary restraint agreements, which has been in effect since October 1984, should be extended for at least another five years,'' said the <ORGANIZATION> AISI </ORGANIZATION> said in a printed statement. The American producers said the quotas program `` has fallen short of its objective for the almost four-year period of its implementation.'' Excluding semi-finished steel, January through May imports totaled 7.8 million tons, or 17.8 percent of apparent domestic consumption. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> set a limit of 18.5 percent market penetration when he initiated the quotas. American steelmakers imported about 238,000 tons out of the 1.93 million tons imported in May, the New York-based <ORGANIZATION> AIIS </ORGANIZATION> said. `` Steel imports have been a critical support for American steel producers, who could contiue to meet demand as a result of imported steel slab,'' said <PERSON> Erwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Klein </PERSON>, AIIS president and vice chairman of the importing firm <ORGANIZATION> Steelinter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>. `` Industry and government should carefully review the fact that imports relieve shortages and cut costs.''
