<HEAD>Grain Futures End Wild Week With A Whimper</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Conflicting weather forecasts for the drought-stricken Farm Belt brought a wild week of grain trading to a fairly subdued close Friday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>. Soybeans posted strong gains but corn and wheat were mixed. On other markets, pork bellies surged the limit for daily trading; precious metals were slightly higher; energy futures were mixed; and stock index futures advanced. Forecasts for next week's weather were so mixed that `` every time I pick up the telephone I hear a different one,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Frazier </PERSON>, Chicago-based grain specialist with <ORGANIZATION> Balfour </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maclaine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. Temperatures soared above 100 degrees Friday afternoon in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and some private meteorologists were calling for dry conditions and searing temperatures to linger in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> through Thursday. But other private forecasters expected cooler temperatures and scattered showers to move into the region this weekend. `` We're in the hands of the weather and the weatherman,'' <PERSON> Frazier </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>, grain specialist with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, agreed: `` People are not sure we're not going to get another rain front in the middle of next week, and the markets are very, very nervous.'' The drought has taken a heavy toll on the corn crop. The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> estimated in a report on Tuesday that 1988 corn production would fall 27 percent below last year, and the damage mounted during the week as the stunted crop neared the end of its pollination stage. Soybeans will enter a critical growing period within two weeks, analysts said. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> report predicted a 14 percent drop in soybean production, based on Tuesday's conditions. Friday's mixed close ended a week marked by wide swings in prices. Soybeans for July delivery ranged during the week from $ 8.56 to $ 10.20 a bushel and July corn ranged from $ 2.86 to $ 3.50 a bushel. Heavy profit-taking dragged soybeans down to a 5-week low on Monday. But the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> crop report renewed fears of heavy yield losses, and traders responded by bidding prices back up to levels close to the previous week's highs. Wheat settled 4 cents lower to 5 cents higher with the contract for delivery in July at $ 3.84 a bushel; corn was 7 cents lower to 1 -RCB- cents higher with July at $ 3.33 -LCB- a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 7 -LCB- cents higher with July at $ 3.11 -LCB- a bushel; soybeans were 7 -LCB- cents to 32 cents higher with July at $ 9.94 -LCB- a bushel. Frozen pork belly futures continued their recovery from recent lows near 32 cents a pound amid higher cash prices and retail featuring of bacon, analysts said. Friday's gain of 2 cents a pound _ the maximum allowed _ on contracts for July and August delivery marked the fourth straight day of the pork belly rally on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. A decline in hog slaughter numbers lent additional support to the belly and hog futures, said <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Durchholz </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> AgriVisor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bloomington </LOCATION>, Ill. Most cattle futures advanced in pre-weekend position-squaring, analysts said. Live cattle were .15 cent lower to .85 cent higher with August at 64.27 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .80 cent higher with August at 74.75 cents a pound; hogs were .25 cent lower to .75 cent higher with July at 46.27 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .68 cent to 2 cents higher with July at 37.30 cents a pound. The soaring dollar kept a lid on the precious metals market despite the possibility that Peruvian silver miners will launch a nationwide strike on Monday. The dollar soared against several currencies in reaction to the government's report of a $ 10.9 billion merchandise trade deficit in May. `` This was a fantastically strong dollar,'' said <PERSON> Bette </PERSON> <PERSON> Raptopoulos </PERSON>, precious metals analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` It just surged and put pressure on outside markets.'' Gold settled $ 1 to $ 1.40 higher with August at $ 441.30 a troy ounce; silver was 3 cents higher across the board with July at $ 7.31 a troy ounce. Energy futures finished mixed on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in light pre-weekend trading that brokers attributed largely to internal market influences. West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 16 cents lower to 10 cents higher with August at $ 14.86 a barrel; heating oil was .21 cent to .45 cent higher with August at 41.12 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .91 cent lower to .01 cent higher with August at 49.73 cents a gallon. Stock-index futures advanced slightly on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, where the contract for September delivery of the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500 index settled 1.35 points higher at 272.80.
