<HEAD>Congressman Battles British Takeover of Insurance Company</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AT-1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> lawmaker on Friday charged that British <ORGANIZATION> BAT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 4.5 billion bid for <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> threatens jobs and anti-smoking efforts and urged state regulators to reject the move. `` I have serious doubts about whether we should permit ... hostile takeovers of American companies by foreign firms, which are not motivated by a long-term commitment to the maintenance of American jobs or the well-being of the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people,'' said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> Democrat. The bid must be approved by nine states in which the insurance company operates. <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> have rejected the bid. But <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> said litigation is planned in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. A spokesman for BAT Industries' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> subsidiary, the <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, Ky.-based <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, could not be reached for comment. But the company said in a statement that it has extended to Aug. 11 the deadline of its tender offer to purchase all of Farmers' outstanding common shares for $ 63 each BAT is the world's largest tobacco company; Farmers, based in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, is a leading <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> insurance company. Hostile takeovers `` have consumed larger and larger shares of American capital and productive capacity,'' <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> said, calling takeovers by foreign-owned companies particularly worrisome. Farmers has 1,940 <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> employees, 2,000 agents and more than 1.26 million policy holders in the state. <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> said the takeover would `` jeopardize the jobs of employees and the security of policyholders in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>,'' many of whom have taken advantage of premium discounts for non-smokers. BAT `` has indicated it does not approve of and would not continue Farmers' health-oriented, money-saving, anti-smoking efforts,'' <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> said. Besides offering discounts to non-smokers, the insurance company produces anti-smoking literature.
