 Stock prices chalked up a moderate gain Friday in a restrained response to what most analysts described as favorable news on international trade. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 15.83 to 2,129.45, finishing the week with a net gain of 23.30. Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 5 to 4 in nationwide trading of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> Exchange-listed stocks, with 787 up, 632 down and 532 unchanged. Volume on the floor of the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> came to 199.71 million shares, up from 172.41 million in the previous session. Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter market, totaled 225.86 million shares. The market registered a slight favorable response to the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report that the merchandise trade deficit in May stood at $ 10.9 billion, a bit below most advance estimates. The dollar gave the news a particularly warm reception, posting strong gains against leading foreign currencies. However, analysts also noted that the deficit figure for April was revised upward to $ 10.3 billion from $ 9.9 billion. In other economic news, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said wholesale prices rose 0.4 percent in June. That too came in lower than expected, considering the surge in prices of many farm commodities as a result of the drought. Industrial production rose 0.4 percent in June, for the ninth consecutive month without a decline, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> said. International Business Machines gained -RCB- to 125 -LCB-. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s second-quarter earnings came in about as expected, up 12.7 percent excluding a special restruc