<HEAD>Bond Prices Edge Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bond prices edged higher in moderate trading Friday as investors reacted to a surge in the dollar following the government's report that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit for May had not worsened considerably. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s bellwether 30-year bond rose about \ point, or about $ 2.50 for every $ 1,000 in face amount. Its yield, which moves inversely to its price, slipped to 9.14 percent from 9.17 percent late Thursday. Long bond prices made the biggest gains, but trading in those securities was light, said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, director of money market research for <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The bond market had been sluggish during the week in anticipation of three key economic reports _ on the trade deficit, producer prices and industrial production, all released Friday morning. But all of the reports were about as expected, and as a result had little impact on bond prices, analysts said. They said bond prices got a push, however, from the dollar's rise in foreign exchange markets. `` There were really no jolts or surprises as far as the economic data,'' <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said. `` But the international markets interpreted the trade figures very bullishly and the dollar moved up smartly. The dollar's firmer trend helped support higher bond prices.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported the deficit widened to $ 10.9 billion in May, from a revised April figure of $ 10.3 billion. Analysts had expected the trade gap would expand to the $ 11 billion area. The $ 10.9 billion imbalance was the second lowest in almost three years. `` The continued improved trend in the trade figures and strength in the dollar as a result of them have temporarily offset fears of higher short-term interest rates,'' said <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> B. Front, an economist at the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> investment and mutual-fund management firm of <ORGANIZATION> Stein </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <LOCATION> Farnham </LOCATION>. A sharp widening of the trade gap in the past has hurt the dollar and led to declines in bond prices. Bond investors fear a lower dollar will lead to inflation, credit-tightening by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> and surging interest rates. A moderate 0.4 percent rise for June in the government's Producer Price Index also boosted investor confidence, Front said `` Bond prices were up modestly reflecting a sense of relief that the trade figures and the Producer Price Index did n't provide any important shocks and did n't reveal any negatives,'' he said. In the secondary market for <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bonds, prices of short-term government issues rose about 1-16 point, intermediate maturities rose by between -LRB- point to 7-32 point and 20-year issues were up 5-32 point, according to the financial information service <ORGANIZATION> Telerate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $ 10 in the price of a bond with a $ 1,000 face value. The <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Bond Index, which measures price movements on all outstanding <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> issues with maturities of a year or longer, was up 1.61 to 1,138.97. <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION>'s Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures price movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, rose 0.65 to 281.88. Among tax-exempt municipal bonds, general obligations were unchanged while dollar bonds were up \ point. Trading was moderate. Three-month <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bills were down 1 basis point to a discounted rate of 6.71 percent, for a yield of 6.91 percent. Six-month bills rose 4 basis points to a discounted rate of 7.05 percent to yield 7.40 percent and one-year bills were unchanged at 7.26 percent to yield 7.77 percent. A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield is the annualized return on an investment in a <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bill. The discounted rate is the interest rate the market uses to price bills. The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, was quoted at 7 13-16 percent, up from 7 -RCB- percent late Thursday.
