<HEAD>Gannett Earnings Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday that earnings advanced 9 percent in the second quarter, thanks in part to a favorable change in the company's tax rate Net income was $ 97.5 million compared to $ 89.7 million for the same period a year ago. Earnings per share increased to 60 cents from 56 cents for the same quarter the year before. Operating revenues advanced 7 percent to $ 846.9 million, compared to $ 789.8 million. For the first half of 1988, net income increased 21 percent to $ 171.5 million. Operating revenues gained 8 percent to $ 1.6 billion. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Curley </PERSON>, president and chief executive officer, said, `` Most <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> units achieved higher earnings, despite an uncertain economic environment which affected advertising volume. `` Newspaper operations reported increased earnings in the quarter and the trend in outdoor advertising improved. Broadcasting earnings were impacted by weak national sales and the company's continuing investment in <ORGANIZATION> GTG </ORGANIZATION> entertainment. <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> is a nationwide news and information company that publishes 89 daily newspapers, including <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Today </ORGANIZATION>, 35 non-daily newspapers and <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weekend </ORGANIZATION>, a newspaper magazine. The company said ad revenues at <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Today </ORGANIZATION> advanced 6 percent as a result of a rate adjustment. Paid advertising pages for the newspaper declined slightly in the quarter. It operates 10 television stations, 16 radio stations, <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and the largest outdoor advertising company in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.
