<HEAD>Coca-Cola's Profit Up 13.8 Percent in Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> reported Thursday that its profit rose 13.8 percent in the second quarter from a year earlier, led by strong sales in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> that were helped by the weaker dollar. The beverage maker and distributor said net income increased to $ 303 million, or 82 cents a share, from $ 266.4 million, or 70 cents a share, in the second quarter of 1987. Second-quarter revenue rose 9.9 percent, to $ 2.3 billion from $ 2.1 billion a year earlier. For the first six months of the year, <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION>'s profit jumped 13.7 percent, to $ 513.6 million, or $ 1.39 a share, from $ 451.8 million, or $ 1.19 a share, in the first half of 1987. Revenue for the half expanded 14.5 percent, to $ 4.2 billion from $ 3.6 billion. `` The excellent second-quarter results reaffirm our expectation that 1988 will be another year of strong volume and solid, double-digit earnings growth for our company, coming on top of a record 1987,'' <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Goizueta </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer, said in a press statement. `` Our core soft drink business has never been on more solid ground by any measure,'' he said. `` We expect the next six months to benefit from the strong momentum with which our business is moving into the second half of this year.'' The company said its worldwide soft drink unit sales increased 5 percent in the latest quarter and 7 percent in the first six months. Outside the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, second-quarter soft drink volume grew an average 5 percent, including advances of 8 percent in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and 6 percent in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>. The dollar's decline against key foreign currencies boosted <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION> sales by making the product cheaper overseas, the company said. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sales in the quarter grew 6 percent, including a 9 percent rise in shipments of Coca-Cola Classic.
