<HEAD>Oregon Official Rejects Proposed Farmers Insurance Takeover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Oregon's insurance commissioner on Thursday rejected <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s attempted hostile takeover of the <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> unit of <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Commissioner <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Kulongoski </PERSON> concluded that the proposed buyout by <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> arm of British conglomerate <ORGANIZATION> BAT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> would affect Farmers' policyholders adversely and be harmful to free competition in the <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> insurance trade <PERSON> Kulongoski </PERSON> also cited the intention of <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION>, which owns a major tobacco company, to restrict the non-smoker policies sold by Farmers. The commissioner said that also would be bad for competition. <PERSON> Kulongoski </PERSON>'s order can be appealed to the courts. <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION> has offered about $ 4.5 billion to acquire Los Angeles-based Farmers. Farmers directors have rejected the proposal, which would require approval of insurance regulators in nine states where Farmers has units. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s insurance commissioner also has rejected the proposal, and <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> has approved it. The commissioner's ruling stated the proposed acquisition `` subjects policyholders and shareholders to substantial risks while providing no benefit that Farmers does not already enjoy.'' He also said the continued denials by BAT and <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION> `` of the known adverse health effects of tobacco smoking, and its stated intentions of precluding Farmers from referring to such health effects in its marketing literature, do not promote the interest of the insurance-buying public.'' <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION> owns <ORGANIZATION> Brown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Williamson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tobacco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> along with department store concerns including <ORGANIZATION> Saks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fifth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Avenue </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Marshall </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Kulongoski </PERSON> said the proposed purchase would increase risks to Farmers' policyholders because of potential judgments over liability lawsuits involving tobacco products. `` In addition,'' <PERSON> Kulongoski </PERSON> said, `` there is evidence that the proposed financing of the acquisition is unworkable.'' And he said the takeover would be `` detrimental to free competition in the <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> insurance marketplace.''
