<HEAD>Aerospace Company Says 6 Pct. Profit Increase Due to Tax Cut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALABASAS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> reported a 6 percent profit second quarter profit increase on Thursday, but the aerospace company attributed the gain largely to lower taxes. <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> earned $ 106 million, or $ 1.77 per share, in the second quarter, up from $ 100 million, or $ 1.51 per share, in the same period of 1987. Sales during the quarter ended June 26 fell to $ 2.7 billion from $ 2.9 billion the year before. The per-share earnings figures for the two years are not comparable because the company has bought back some 7 million shares of its stock since the October 1987 stock market crash. Operating profit declined in the second quarter, to $ 163 million from $ 195 million, partly because <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION>'s contract to build the C-5B military transport plane is nearing an end, the company said. Additionally, new Pentagon policies requiring contractors to pay a larger share of the cost of development contracts has reduced operating profit, the company said. Net income rose primarily because of lower tax rates, said <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Kitchen </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive. In the first half of 1988, <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> reported a profit of $ 220 million on sales of $ 5.3 billion, up from profit of $ 186 million on sales of $ 5.4 billion in the same period of 1987.
